# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: combustion
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] The International Agency for Research on Cancer (IARC) has listed acetaldehyde as a Group 1 carcinogen.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is "one of the most frequently found air toxins with cancer risk greater than one in a million".
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] In 1835, Liebig named it "aldehyde", and in the middle of the century the name was altered to "acetaldehyde".
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] In 2013, global production was about 438,000 tonnes.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Before 1962, ethanol and acetylene were the major sources of acetaldehyde.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Since then, ethylene is the dominant feedstock.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] In the 1970s, the world capacity of the Wacker-Hoechst direct oxidation process exceeded two million tonnes annually.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Smaller quantities can be prepared by the partial oxidation of ethanol in an exothermic reaction.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] This process typically is conducted over a silver catalyst at about 500–650 °C (950–1,200 °F).
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] This method is one of the oldest routes for the industrial preparation of acetaldehyde.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Prior to the Wacker process and the availability of cheap ethylene, acetaldehyde was produced by the hydration of acetylene.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] The mechanism involves the intermediacy of vinyl alcohol, which tautomerizes to acetaldehyde.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] The reaction is conducted at 90–95 °C (194–203 °F), and the acetaldehyde formed is separated from water and mercury and cooled to 25–30 °C (77–86 °F).
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] In the wet oxidation process, iron(III) sulfate is used to reoxidize the mercury back to the mercury(II) salt.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] The resulting iron(II) sulfate is oxidized in a separate reactor with nitric acid.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] The enzyme Acetylene hydratase discovered in the strictly anaerobic bacterium *Pelobacter acetylenicus* can catalyze an analogous reaction without involving any compounds of mercury.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] However, it has thus far not been brought to any large-scale or commercial use.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] In this endothermic process, ethanol vapor is passed at 260–290 °C over a copper-based catalyst.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] The process was once attractive because of the value of the hydrogen coproduct, but in modern times is not economically viable.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] The hydroformylation of methanol with catalysts like cobalt, nickel, or iron salts also produces acetaldehyde, although this process is of no industrial importance.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Similarly noncompetitive, acetaldehyde arises from synthesis gas with modest selectivity.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] The equilibrium constant is 6×10−7 at room temperature, thus that the relative amount of the enol form in a sample of acetaldehyde is very small.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] At room temperature, acetaldehyde (CH3CH=O) is more stable than vinyl alcohol (CH2=CHOH) by 42.7 kJ/mol: Overall the keto-enol tautomerization occurs slowly but is catalyzed by acids.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Photo-induced keto-enol tautomerization is viable under atmospheric or stratospheric conditions.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] This photo-tautomerization is relevant to the Earth's atmosphere, because vinyl alcohol is thought to be a precursor to carboxylic acids in the atmosphere.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is a common electrophile in organic synthesis.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] In addition reactions acetaldehyde is prochiral.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] It is used primarily as a source of the "CH3C+H(OH)" synthon in aldol reactions and related condensation reactions.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Grignard reagents and organolithium compounds react with MeCHO to give hydroxyethyl derivatives.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] In one of the more spectacular addition reactions, formaldehyde in the presence of calcium hydroxide adds to MeCHO to give pentaerythritol, C(CH2OH)4 and formate.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] In a Strecker reaction, acetaldehyde condenses with cyanide and ammonia to give, after hydrolysis, the amino acid alanine.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde can condense with amines to yield imines; for example, with cyclohexylamine to give *N*-ethylidenecyclohexylamine.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] These imines can be used to direct subsequent reactions like an aldol condensation.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] It is also a building block in the synthesis of heterocyclic compounds.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] In one example, it converts, upon treatment with ammonia, to 5-ethyl-2-methylpyridine ("aldehyde-collidine").
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Three molecules of acetaldehyde condense to form "paraldehyde", a cyclic trimer containing C-O single bonds.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Similarly condensation of four molecules of acetaldehyde give the cyclic molecule metaldehyde.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Paraldehyde can be produced in good yields, using a sulfuric acid catalyst.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Metaldehyde is only obtained in a few percent yield and with cooling, often using HBr rather than H2SO4 as the catalyst.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] At −40 °C (−40 °F) in the presence of acid catalysts, polyacetaldehyde is produced.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] There are two stereomers of paraldehyde and four of metaldehyde.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] The German chemist Valentin Hermann Weidenbusch (1821–1893) synthesized paraldehyde in 1848 by treating acetaldehyde with acid (either sulfuric or nitric acid) and cooling to 0 °C (32 °F).
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] He found it quite remarkable that when paraldehyde was *heated* with a trace of the same acid, the reaction went the other way, recreating acetaldehyde.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Although vinyl alcohol is a tautomeric form of acetaldehyde (§ Tautomerization to vinyl alcohol), polyvinyl alcohol cannot be produced from acetaldehyde.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde forms a stable acetal upon reaction with ethanol under conditions that favor dehydration.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] The product, CH3CH(OCH2CH3)2, is formally named 1,1-diethoxyethane but is commonly referred to as "acetal".
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] This can cause confusion as "acetal" is more commonly used to describe compounds with the functional groups RCH(OR')2 or RR'C(OR'')2 rather than referring to this specific compound — in fact, 1,1-diethoxyethane is also described as the diethyl acetal of acetaldehyde.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is a precursor to vinylphosphonic acid, which is used to make adhesives and ion conductive membranes.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] In the liver, the enzyme alcohol dehydrogenase oxidizes ethanol into acetaldehyde, which is then further oxidized into harmless acetic acid by acetaldehyde dehydrogenase.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] These two oxidation reactions are coupled with the reduction of NAD+ to NADH.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] In the brain, the enzyme catalase is primarily responsible for oxidizing ethanol to acetaldehyde, and alcohol dehydrogenase plays a minor role.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] The last steps of alcoholic fermentation in bacteria, plants, and yeast involve the conversion of pyruvate into acetaldehyde and carbon dioxide by the enzyme pyruvate decarboxylase, followed by the conversion of acetaldehyde into ethanol.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] The latter reaction is again catalyzed by an alcohol dehydrogenase, now operating in the opposite direction.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Many East Asian people have an ALDH2 mutation which makes them significantly less efficient at oxidizing acetaldehyde.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] On consuming alcohol, their bodies tend to accumulate excessive amounts of acetaldehyde, causing the so-called alcohol flush reaction.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] They develop a characteristic flush on the face and body, along with "nausea, headache and general physical discomfort".
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Ingestion of the drug disulfiram, which inhibits ALDH2, leads to a similar reaction .
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Traditionally, acetaldehyde was mainly used as a precursor to acetic acid.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] This application has declined because acetic acid is produced more efficiently from methanol by the Monsanto and Cativa processes.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is an important precursor to pyridine derivatives, pentaerythritol, and crotonaldehyde.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Urea and acetaldehyde combine to give a useful resin.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Acetic anhydride reacts with acetaldehyde to give ethylidene diacetate, a precursor to vinyl acetate, which is used to produce polyvinyl acetate.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] The global market for acetaldehyde is declining.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Demand has been impacted by changes in the production of plasticizer alcohols, which has shifted because *n*-butyraldehyde is less often produced from acetaldehyde, instead being generated by hydroformylation of propylene.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Likewise, acetic acid, once produced from acetaldehyde, is made predominantly by the lower-cost methanol carbonylation process.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] The impact on demand has led to increase in prices and thus slowdown in the market.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] China is the largest consumer of acetaldehyde in the world, accounting for almost half of global consumption in 2012.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Major use has been the production of acetic acid.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Other uses such as pyridines and pentaerythritol are expected to grow faster than acetic acid, but the volumes are not large enough to offset the decline in acetic acid.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] As a consequence, overall acetaldehyde consumption in China may grow slightly at 1.6% per year through 2018.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Western Europe is the second-largest consumer of acetaldehyde worldwide, accounting for 20% of world consumption in 2012.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] As with China, the Western European acetaldehyde market is expected to increase only very slightly at 1% per year during 2012–2018.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] However, Japan could emerge as a potential consumer for acetaldehyde in the next five years due to newfound use in commercial production of butadiene.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] The supply of butadiene has been volatile in Japan and the rest of Asia.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] This should provide the much needed boost to the flat market, as of 2013.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] The threshold limit value is 25 ppm (STEL/ceiling value) and the MAK (Maximum Workplace Concentration) is 50 ppm.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] At 50 ppm acetaldehyde, no irritation or local tissue damage in the nasal mucosa is observed.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] When taken up by the organism, acetaldehyde is metabolized rapidly in the liver to acetic acid.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Only a small proportion is exhaled unchanged.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] After intravenous injection, the half-life in the blood is approximately 90 seconds.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Many serious cases of acute intoxication have been recorded.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde naturally breaks down in the human body.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is an irritant of the skin, eyes, mucous membranes, throat, and respiratory tract.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] This occurs at concentrations as low as 1000 ppm.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Symptoms of exposure to this compound include nausea, vomiting, and headache.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] These symptoms may not happen immediately.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] The perception threshold for acetaldehyde in air is in the range between 0.07 and 0.25 ppm.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] At such concentrations, the fruity odor of acetaldehyde is apparent.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Conjunctival irritations have been observed after a 15-minute exposure to concentrations of 25 and 50 ppm, but transient conjunctivitis and irritation of the respiratory tract have been reported after exposure to 200 ppm acetaldehyde for 15 minutes.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] In addition, acetaldehyde is damaging to DNA and causes abnormal muscle development as it binds to proteins.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde induces DNA interstrand crosslinks, a form of DNA damage.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] These can be repaired by either of two replication-coupled DNA repair pathways.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] The first is referred to as the FA pathway, because it employs gene products defective in Fanconi's anemia patients.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] This repair pathway results in increased mutation frequency and altered mutational spectrum.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] The second repair pathway requires replication fork convergence, breakage of the acetaldehyde crosslink, translesion synthesis by a Y-family DNA polymerase and homologous recombination.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] People with a genetic deficiency for the enzyme responsible for the conversion of acetaldehyde into acetic acid may have a greater risk of Alzheimer's disease.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] A study of 818 heavy drinkers found that those exposed to more acetaldehyde than normal through a genetic variant of the gene encoding for ADH1C, ADH1C*1, are at greater risk of developing cancers of the upper gastrointestinal tract and liver.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] The drug disulfiram (Antabuse) inhibits acetaldehyde dehydrogenase, an enzyme that oxidizes the compound into acetic acid.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Metabolism of ethanol forms acetaldehyde before acetaldehyde dehydrogenase forms acetic acid, but with the enzyme inhibited, acetaldehyde accumulates.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] If one consumes ethanol while taking disulfiram, the hangover effect of ethanol is felt more rapidly and intensely (disulfiram-alcohol reaction).
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] As such, disulfiram is sometimes used as a deterrent for alcoholics wishing to stay sober.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is a potential contaminant in workplace, indoors, and ambient environments.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Moreover, the majority of humans spend more than 90% of their time in indoor environments, increasing any exposure and the risk to human health.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] In a study in France, the mean indoor concentration of acetaldehydes measured in 16 homes was approximately seven times higher than the outside acetaldehyde concentration.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] The living room had a mean of 18.1±17.5 μg m−3 and the bedroom was 18.2±16.9 μg m−3, whereas the outdoor air had a mean concentration of 2.3±2.6 μg m−3.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] It has been concluded that volatile organic compounds (VOC) such as benzene, formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, toluene, and xylenes have to be considered priority pollutants with respect to their health effects.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] It has been pointed that in renovated or completely new buildings, the VOCs concentration levels are often several orders of magnitude higher.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] The main sources of acetaldehydes in homes include building materials, laminate, PVC flooring, varnished wood flooring, and varnished cork/pine flooring (found in the varnish, not the wood).
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] It is also found in plastics, oil-based and water-based paints, in composite wood ceilings, particle-board, plywood, treated pine wood, and laminated chipboard furniture.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] The use of acetaldehyde is widespread in different industries, and it may be released into waste water or the air during production, use, transportation and storage.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Sources of acetaldehyde include fuel combustion emissions from stationary internal combustion engines and power plants that burn fossil fuels, wood, or trash, oil and gas extraction, refineries, cement kilns, lumber and wood mills and paper mills.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is also present in automobile and diesel exhaust.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] As a result, acetaldehyde is "one of the most frequently found air toxics with cancer risk greater than one in a million".
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Natural tobacco polysaccharides, including cellulose, have been shown to be the primary precursors making acetaldehyde a significant constituent of tobacco smoke.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] It has been demonstrated to have a synergistic effect with nicotine in rodent studies of addiction.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is also the most abundant carcinogen in tobacco smoke; it is dissolved into the saliva while smoking.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde has been found in cannabis smoke.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] This finding emerged through the use of new chemical techniques that demonstrated the acetaldehyde present was causing DNA damage in laboratory settings.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Many microbes produce acetaldehyde from ethanol, but they have a lower capacity to eliminate the acetaldehyde, which can lead to the accumulation of acetaldehyde in saliva, stomach acid, and intestinal contents.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Fermented food and many alcoholic beverages can also contain significant amounts of acetaldehyde.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde, derived from mucosal or microbial oxidation of ethanol, tobacco smoke, and diet, appears to act as a cumulative carcinogen in the upper digestive tract of humans.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] According to European Commission's Scientific Committee on Consumer Safety's (SCCS) "Opinion on Acetaldehyde" (2012) the cosmetic products special risk limit is 5 mg/L and acetaldehyde should not be used in mouth-washing products.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde can be produced by the photo-oxidation of polyethylene terephthalate (PET), via a Type II Norrish reaction.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] Although the levels produced by this process are minute acetaldehyde has an exceedingly low taste/odor threshold of around 20–40 ppb and can cause an off-taste in bottled water.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] The level at which an average consumer could detect acetaldehyde is still considerably lower than any toxicity.
[src:combustion/acetaldehyde] The yeast *Candida albicans* in patients with potentially carcinogenic oral diseases has been shown to produce acetaldehyde in quantities sufficient to cause problems.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] In the Arrhenius model of reaction rates, **activation energy** is the minimum amount of energy that must be available to reactants for a chemical reaction to occur.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] The activation energy (*E*a) of a reaction is measured in kilojoules per mole (kJ/mol) or kilocalories per mole (kcal/mol).
[src:combustion/activation-energy] Activation energy is the minimum energy barrier that reactant molecules must overcome to transform into products.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] A reaction occurs only if enough molecules have kinetic energy equal to or greater than this barrier, which usually requires sufficiently high temperature.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] The term "activation energy" was introduced in 1889 by the Swedish scientist Svante Arrhenius.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] Although less commonly used, activation energy also applies to nuclear reactions and various other physical phenomena.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] The Arrhenius equation gives the quantitative basis of the relationship between the activation energy and the rate at which a reaction proceeds.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] where *A* is the pre-exponential factor for the reaction, *R* is the universal gas constant, *T* is the absolute temperature (usually in kelvins), and *k* is the reaction rate coefficient.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] Even without knowing *A*, *E*a can be evaluated from the variation in reaction rate coefficients as a function of temperature (within the validity of the Arrhenius equation).
[src:combustion/activation-energy] At a more advanced level, the net Arrhenius activation energy term from the Arrhenius equation is best regarded as an experimentally determined parameter that indicates the sensitivity of the reaction rate to temperature.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] There are two objections to associating this activation energy with the threshold barrier for an elementary reaction.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] First, it is often unclear as to whether or not reaction does proceed in one step; threshold barriers that are averaged out over all elementary steps have little theoretical value.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] A substance that modifies the transition state to lower the activation energy is termed a catalyst; a catalyst composed only of protein and (if applicable) small molecule cofactors is termed an enzyme.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] A catalyst increases the rate of reaction without being consumed in the reaction.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] In addition, the catalyst lowers the activation energy, but it does not change the energies of the original reactants or products, and so does not change equilibrium.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] Rather, the reactant energy and the product energy remain the same and only the *activation energy* is altered (lowered).
[src:combustion/activation-energy] A catalyst is able to reduce the activation energy by forming a transition state in a more favorable manner.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] Catalysts, by nature, create a more "comfortable" fit for the substrate of a reaction to progress to a transition state.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] This is possible due to a release of energy that occurs when the substrate binds to the active site of a catalyst.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] Upon binding to a catalyst, substrates partake in numerous stabilizing forces while within the active site (e.g. hydrogen bonding or van der Waals forces).
[src:combustion/activation-energy] Specific and favorable bonding occurs within the active site until the substrate forms to become the high-energy transition state.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] Forming the transition state is more favorable with the catalyst because the favorable stabilizing interactions within the active site *release* energy.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] A chemical reaction is able to manufacture a high-energy transition state molecule more readily when there is a stabilizing fit within the active site of a catalyst.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] The binding energy of a reaction is this energy released when favorable interactions between substrate and catalyst occur.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] The binding energy released assists in achieving the unstable transition state.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] Reactions without catalysts need a higher input of energy to achieve the transition state.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] Non-catalyzed reactions do not have free energy available from active site stabilizing interactions, such as catalytic enzyme reactions.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] In the Arrhenius equation, the term activation energy (*E*a) is used to describe the energy required to reach the transition state, and the exponential relationship *k* = *A* exp(−*E*a/*RT*) holds.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] In transition state theory, a more sophisticated model of the relationship between reaction rates and the transition state, a superficially similar mathematical relationship, the Eyring equation, is used to describe the rate constant of a reaction: *k* = (*k*B*T* / *h*) exp(−Δ*G*‡ / *RT*).
[src:combustion/activation-energy] However, instead of modeling the temperature dependence of reaction rate phenomenologically, the Eyring equation models individual elementary steps of a reaction.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] Thus, for a multistep process, there is no straightforward relationship between the two models.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] Nevertheless, the functional forms of the Arrhenius and Eyring equations are similar, and for a one-step process, simple and chemically meaningful correspondences can be drawn between Arrhenius and Eyring parameters.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] Instead of also using *E*a, the Eyring equation uses the concept of Gibbs energy and the symbol Δ*G*‡ to denote the Gibbs energy of activation to achieve the transition state.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] In the equation, *k*B and *h* are the Boltzmann and Planck constants, respectively.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] Although the equations look similar, the Gibbs energy contains an entropic term in addition to the enthalpic one.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] In the Arrhenius equation, this entropic term is accounted for by the pre-exponential factor *A*.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] More specifically, we can write the Gibbs free energy of activation in terms of enthalpy and entropy of activation: Δ*G*‡ = Δ*H*‡ − *T* Δ*S*‡.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] Then, for a unimolecular, one-step reaction, the *approximate* relationships *E*a = Δ*H*‡ + *RT* and *A* = (*k*B*T*/*h*) exp(1 + Δ*S*‡/*R*) hold.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] Note, however, that in Arrhenius theory proper, *A* is temperature independent, while here, there is a linear dependence on *T*.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] For a one-step unimolecular process whose half-life at room temperature is about 2 hours, Δ*G*‡ is approximately 23 kcal/mol.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] This is also the roughly the magnitude of *E*a for a reaction that proceeds over several hours at room temperature.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] Due to the relatively small magnitude of *T*Δ*S*‡ and *RT* at ordinary temperatures for most reactions, in sloppy discourse, *E*a, Δ*G*‡, and Δ*H*‡ are often conflated and all referred to as the "activation energy".
[src:combustion/activation-energy] The enthalpy, entropy and Gibbs energy of activation are more correctly written as Δ‡*H*o, Δ‡*S*o and Δ‡*G*o respectively, where the o indicates a quantity evaluated between standard states.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] However, some authors omit the o in order to simplify the notation.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] The total free energy change of a reaction is independent of the activation energy however.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] Physical and chemical reactions can be either exergonic or endergonic, but the activation energy is not related to the spontaneity of a reaction.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] The overall reaction energy change is not altered by the activation energy.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] In some cases, rates of reaction *decrease* with increasing temperature.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] When following an approximately exponential relationship so the rate constant can still be fit to an Arrhenius expression, this results in a negative value of *E*a.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] Elementary reactions exhibiting negative activation energies are typically barrierless reactions, in which the reaction proceeding relies on the capture of the molecules in a potential well.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] Such a situation no longer leads itself to direct interpretations as the height of a potential barrier.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] Some multistep reactions can also have apparent negative activation energies.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] For example, the overall rate constant k for a two-step reaction A ⇌ B, B → C is given by k = k2K1, where k2 is the rate constant of the rate-limiting slow second step and K1 is the equilibrium constant of the rapid first step.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] In some reactions, K1 decreases with temperature more rapidly than k2 increases, so that k actually decreases with temperature corresponding to a negative observed activation energy.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] An example is the oxidation of nitric oxide which is a termolecular reaction ${\ce {2 NO + O2 -> 2 NO2}}$ .
[src:combustion/activation-energy] Certain cationic polymerization reactions have negative activation energies so that the rate decreases with temperature.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] For chain-growth polymerization, the overall activation energy is $\textstyle E=E_{i}+E_{p}-E_{t}$ , where i, p and t refer respectively to initiation, propagation and termination steps.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] The propagation step normally has a very small activation energy, so that the overall value is negative if the activation energy for termination is larger than that for initiation.
[src:combustion/activation-energy] The normal range of overall activation energies for cationic polymerization varies from 40 to 60 kJ/mol.
[src:combustion/adiabatic-flame-temperature] In the study of combustion, the **adiabatic flame temperature** is the temperature reached by a flame under ideal conditions.
[src:combustion/adiabatic-flame-temperature] It is an upper bound of the temperature that is reached in actual processes.
[src:combustion/adiabatic-flame-temperature] There are two types of adiabatic flame temperature: *constant volume* and *constant pressure*, depending on how the process is completed.
[src:combustion/adiabatic-flame-temperature] The constant volume adiabatic flame temperature is the temperature that results from a complete combustion process that occurs without any work, heat transfer or changes in kinetic or potential energy.
[src:combustion/adiabatic-flame-temperature] Its temperature is higher than in the *constant pressure* process because no energy is utilized to change the volume of the system (i.e., generate work).
[src:combustion/adiabatic-flame-temperature] In daily life, the vast majority of flames one encounters are those caused by rapid oxidation of hydrocarbons in materials such as wood, wax, fat, plastics, propane, and gasoline.
[src:combustion/adiabatic-flame-temperature] The constant-pressure adiabatic flame temperature of such substances in air is in a relatively narrow range around 1,950 °C (2,220 K; 3,540 °F).
[src:combustion/adiabatic-flame-temperature] This is mostly because the heat of combustion of these compounds is roughly proportional to the amount of oxygen consumed, which proportionally increases the amount of air that has to be heated, so the effect of a larger heat of combustion on the flame temperature is offset.
[src:combustion/adiabatic-flame-temperature] Incomplete reaction at higher temperature further curtails the effect of a larger heat of combustion.
[src:combustion/adiabatic-flame-temperature] Because most combustion processes that happen naturally occur in the open air, there is nothing that confines the gas to a particular volume like the cylinder in an engine.
[src:combustion/adiabatic-flame-temperature] As a result, these substances will burn at a constant pressure, which allows the gas to expand during the process.
[src:combustion/adiabatic-flame-temperature] Assuming initial atmospheric conditions (1 bar and 20 °C), the following table lists the flame temperature for various fuels under constant pressure conditions.
[src:combustion/adiabatic-flame-temperature] The temperatures mentioned here are for a stoichiometric fuel-oxidizer mixture (i.e. equivalence ratio *φ* = 1).
[src:combustion/adiabatic-flame-temperature] These are theoretical, not actual, flame temperatures produced by a flame that loses no heat.
[src:combustion/adiabatic-flame-temperature] The closest will be the hottest part of a flame, where the combustion reaction is most efficient.
[src:combustion/adiabatic-flame-temperature] This also assumes complete combustion (e.g. perfectly balanced, non-smoky, usually bluish flame).
[src:combustion/adiabatic-flame-temperature] Several values in the table significantly disagree with the literature or predictions by online calculators.
[src:combustion/adiabatic-flame-temperature] where, ${}_{R}Q_{P}$ and ${}_{R}W_{P}$ are the heat and work transferred from the system to the surroundings during the process, respectively, and $U_{R}$ and $U_{P}$ are the internal energy of the reactants and products, respectively.
[src:combustion/adiabatic-flame-temperature] There is also no heat transfer because the process is defined to be adiabatic: ${}_{R}Q_{P}=0$ .
[src:combustion/adiabatic-flame-temperature] As a result, the internal energy of the products is equal to the internal energy of the reactants: $U_{P}=U_{R}$ .
[src:combustion/adiabatic-flame-temperature] Again there is no heat transfer occurring because the process is defined to be adiabatic: ${}_{R}Q_{P}=0$ .
[src:combustion/adiabatic-flame-temperature] Recalling the definition of enthalpy we obtain $H_{P}=H_{R}$ .
[src:combustion/adiabatic-flame-temperature] We see that the adiabatic flame temperature of the constant pressure process is lower than that of the constant volume process.
[src:combustion/adiabatic-flame-temperature] This is because some of the energy released during combustion goes, as work, into changing the volume of the control system.
[src:combustion/adiabatic-flame-temperature] If we make the assumption that combustion goes to completion (i.e. forming only CO 2 and H 2O), we can calculate the adiabatic flame temperature by hand either at stoichiometric conditions or lean of stoichiometry (excess air).
[src:combustion/adiabatic-flame-temperature] and use the equilibrium constant for this reaction, we will have enough variables to complete the calculation.
[src:combustion/adiabatic-flame-temperature] Different fuels with different levels of energy and molar constituents will have different adiabatic flame temperatures.
[src:combustion/adiabatic-flame-temperature] We can see by the following figure why nitromethane (CH3NO2) is often used as a power boost for cars.
[src:combustion/adiabatic-flame-temperature] Since each molecule of nitromethane contains an oxidant with relatively high-energy bonds between nitrogen and oxygen, it can burn much hotter than hydrocarbons or oxygen-containing methanol.
[src:combustion/adiabatic-flame-temperature] This is analogous to adding pure oxygen, which also raises the adiabatic flame temperature.
[src:combustion/adiabatic-flame-temperature] This in turn allows it to build up more pressure during a constant volume process.
[src:combustion/adiabatic-flame-temperature] The higher the pressure, the more force upon the piston creating more work and more power in the engine.
[src:combustion/adiabatic-flame-temperature] It stays relatively hot rich of stoichiometry because it contains its own oxidant.
[src:combustion/adiabatic-flame-temperature] However, continual running of an engine on nitromethane will eventually melt the piston and/or cylinder because of this higher temperature.
[src:combustion/adiabatic-flame-temperature] In real world applications, complete combustion does not typically occur.
[src:combustion/adiabatic-flame-temperature] Chemistry dictates that dissociation and kinetics will change the composition of the products.
[src:combustion/adiabatic-flame-temperature] There are a number of programs available that can calculate the adiabatic flame temperature taking into account dissociation through equilibrium constants (Stanjan, NASA CEA, AFTP).
[src:combustion/adiabatic-flame-temperature] The following figure illustrates that the effects of dissociation tend to lower the adiabatic flame temperature.
[src:combustion/adiabatic-flame-temperature] This result can be explained through Le Chatelier's principle.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] An **adiabatic process** (*adiabatic* from Ancient Greek ἀδιάβατος*(*adiábatos*)* 'impassable') is a type of thermodynamic process whereby a transfer of energy between the thermodynamic system and its environment is accompanied neither by a transfer of entropy nor of amounts of constituents.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] Unlike an isothermal process, an adiabatic process transfers energy to the surroundings only as work and/or mass flow.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] As a key concept in thermodynamics, the adiabatic process supports the theory that explains the first law of thermodynamics.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] The opposite term to "adiabatic" is *diabatic*.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] Some chemical and physical processes occur too rapidly for energy to enter or leave the system as heat, allowing a convenient "adiabatic approximation".
[src:combustion/adiabatic] For example, the adiabatic flame temperature uses this approximation to calculate the upper limit of flame temperature by assuming combustion loses no heat to its surroundings.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] In meteorology, adiabatic expansion and cooling of moist air, which can be triggered by winds flowing up and over a mountain for example, can cause the water vapor pressure to exceed the saturation vapor pressure.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] Expansion and cooling beyond the saturation vapor pressure is often idealized as a *pseudo-adiabatic process* whereby excess vapor instantly precipitates into water droplets.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] The change in temperature of air undergoing pseudo-adiabatic expansion differs from air undergoing adiabatic expansion because latent heat is released by precipitation.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] A process without transfer of thermal energy (heat) to or from a system, so that *Q* = 0, is called adiabatic, and such a system is said to be adiabatically isolated.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] The simplifying assumption frequently made is that a process is adiabatic.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] For example, the compression of a gas within a cylinder of an engine is assumed to occur so rapidly that on the time scale of the compression process, little of the system's energy can be transferred out as heat to the surroundings.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] Even though the cylinders are not insulated and are quite conductive, that process is idealized to be adiabatic.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] The same can be said to be true for the expansion process of such a system.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] The assumption of adiabatic isolation is useful and often combined with other such idealizations to calculate a good first approximation of a system's behaviour.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] For example, according to Laplace, when sound travels in a gas, there is no time for heat conduction in the medium, and so the propagation of sound is adiabatic.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] For such an adiabatic process, the modulus of elasticity (Young's modulus) can be expressed as *E* = *γP*, where γ is the ratio of specific heats at constant pressure and at constant volume ( *γ* = ⁠*Cp*/*Cv*⁠) and *P* is the pressure of the gas.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] For a closed system, one may write the first law of thermodynamics as Δ*U* = *Q* − *W*, where Δ*U* denotes the change of the system's internal energy, Q the quantity of energy added to it as heat, and W the work done by the system on its surroundings.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] Naturally occurring adiabatic processes are irreversible (entropy is produced).
[src:combustion/adiabatic] The transfer of energy as work into an adiabatically isolated system can be imagined as being of two idealized extreme kinds.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] In one such kind, no entropy is produced within the system (no friction, viscous dissipation, etc.), and the work is only pressure-volume work (denoted by *P* d*V*).
[src:combustion/adiabatic] In nature, this ideal kind occurs only approximately because it demands an infinitely slow process and no sources of dissipation.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] The other extreme kind of work is isochoric work (d*V* = 0), for which energy is added as work solely through friction or viscous dissipation within the system.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] A stirrer that transfers energy to a viscous fluid of an adiabatically isolated system with rigid walls, without phase change, will cause a rise in temperature of the fluid, but that work is not recoverable.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] The second law of thermodynamics observes that a natural process, of transfer of energy as work, always consists at least of isochoric work and often both of these extreme kinds of work.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] Every natural process, adiabatic or not, is irreversible, with Δ*S* > 0, as friction or viscosity are always present to some extent.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] The adiabatic compression of a gas causes a rise in temperature of the gas.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] Adiabatic expansion against pressure, or a spring, causes a drop in temperature.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] In contrast, free expansion is an isothermal process for an ideal gas.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] This finds practical application in diesel engines which rely on the lack of heat dissipation during the compression stroke to elevate the fuel vapor temperature sufficiently to ignite it.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] Adiabatic compression occurs in the Earth's atmosphere when an air mass descends, for example, in a Katabatic wind, Foehn wind, or Chinook wind flowing downhill over a mountain range.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] When a parcel of air descends, the pressure on the parcel increases.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] Because of this increase in pressure, the parcel's volume decreases and its temperature increases as work is done on the parcel of air, thus increasing its internal energy, which manifests itself by a rise in the temperature of that mass of air.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] The parcel of air can only slowly dissipate the energy by conduction or radiation (heat), and to a first approximation it can be considered adiabatically isolated and the process an adiabatic process.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] Adiabatic expansion occurs when the pressure on an adiabatically isolated system is decreased, allowing it to expand in size, thus causing it to do work on its surroundings.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] When the pressure applied on a parcel of gas is reduced, the gas in the parcel is allowed to expand; as the volume increases, the temperature falls as its internal energy decreases.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] Adiabatic expansion occurs in the Earth's atmosphere with orographic lifting and lee waves, and this can form pilei or lenticular clouds.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] Due in part to adiabatic expansion in mountainous areas, snowfall actually occurs in some parts of the Sahara desert.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] Adiabatic expansion does not have to involve a fluid.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] One technique used to reach very low temperatures (thousandths and even millionths of a degree above absolute zero) is via adiabatic demagnetisation, where the change in magnetic field on a magnetic material is used to provide adiabatic expansion.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] Also, the contents of an expanding universe can be described (to first order) as an adiabatically expanding fluid.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] Rising magma also undergoes adiabatic expansion before eruption, particularly significant in the case of magmas that rise quickly from great depths such as kimberlites.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] In the Earth's convecting mantle (the asthenosphere) beneath the lithosphere, the mantle temperature is approximately an adiabat.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] The slight decrease in temperature with shallowing depth is due to the decrease in pressure the shallower the material is in the Earth.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] Such temperature changes can be quantified using the ideal gas law, or the hydrostatic equation for atmospheric processes.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] In practice, no process is truly adiabatic.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] Many processes rely on a large difference in time scales of the process of interest and the rate of heat dissipation across a system boundary, and thus are approximated by using an adiabatic assumption.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] There is always some heat loss, as no perfect insulators exist.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] Here CP is the specific heat for constant pressure, CV is the specific heat for constant volume, and f is the number of degrees of freedom (3 for a monatomic gas, 5 for a diatomic gas or a gas of linear molecules such as carbon dioxide).
[src:combustion/adiabatic] For a monatomic ideal gas, *γ* = ⁠5/3⁠, and for a diatomic gas (such as nitrogen and oxygen, the main components of air), *γ* = ⁠7/5⁠.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] Note that the above formula is only applicable to classical ideal gases (that is, gases far above absolute zero temperature) and not Bose–Einstein or Fermi gases.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] where T is the absolute or thermodynamic temperature.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] The compression stroke in a gasoline engine can be used as an example of adiabatic compression.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] so the adiabatic constant for this example is about 6.31 Pa·m4.2 .
[src:combustion/adiabatic] The gas is now compressed to a 0.1 L (0.0001 m3) volume, which we assume happens quickly enough that no heat enters or leaves the gas through the walls.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] We can solve for the temperature of the compressed gas in the engine cylinder as well, using the ideal gas law, P V = n R T (n is amount of gas in moles and R the gas constant for that gas).
[src:combustion/adiabatic] That is a final temperature of 753 K, or 479 °C, or 896 °F, well above the ignition point of many fuels.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] A diesel engine operates under even more extreme conditions, with compression ratios of 16:1 or more being typical, in order to provide a very high gas pressure, which ensures immediate ignition of the injected fuel.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] For an adiabatic free expansion of an ideal gas, the gas is contained in an insulated container and then allowed to expand in a vacuum.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] Because there is no external pressure for the gas to expand against, the work done by or on the system is zero.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] Since this process does not involve any heat transfer or work, the first law of thermodynamics then implies that the net internal energy change of the system is zero.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] For an ideal gas, the temperature remains constant because the internal energy only depends on temperature in that case.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] Since at constant temperature, the entropy is proportional to the volume, the entropy increases in this case, therefore this process is irreversible.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] The definition of an adiabatic process is that heat transfer to the system is zero, *δQ* = 0.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] where d*U* is the change in the internal energy of the system and *δW* is work done *by* the system.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] Any work (*δW*) done must be done at the expense of internal energy U, since no heat δQ is being supplied from the surroundings.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] However, P does not remain constant during an adiabatic process but instead changes along with V.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] It is desired to know how the values of d*P* and d*V* relate to each other as the adiabatic process proceeds.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] where α is the number of degrees of freedom divided by 2, R is the universal gas constant and n is the number of moles in the system (a constant).
[src:combustion/adiabatic] Equation (a4) is often expressed as d*U* = *n CV*d*T* because *CV* = *α R* .
[src:combustion/adiabatic] An adiabat is a curve of constant entropy in a diagram.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] Some properties of adiabats on a *P* – *V* diagram are indicated.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] These properties may be read from the classical behaviour of ideal gases, except in the region where P V becomes small (low temperature), where quantum effects become important.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] Each adiabat intersects each isotherm exactly once.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] An adiabat looks similar to an isotherm, except that during an expansion, an adiabat loses more pressure than an isotherm, so it has a steeper inclination (more vertical).
[src:combustion/adiabatic] If isotherms are concave towards the north-east direction (45° from V axis), then adiabats are concave towards the east north-east (31° from V axisaxis).
[src:combustion/adiabatic] If adiabats and isotherms are graphed at regular intervals of entropy and temperature, respectively (like altitude on a contour map), then as the eye moves towards the axes (towards the south-west), it sees the density of isotherms stay constant, but it sees the density of adiabats grow.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] The exception is very near absolute zero, where the density of adiabats drops sharply and they become rare (see Nernst's theorem).
[src:combustion/adiabatic] The term *adiabatic* (/ˌædiəˈbætɪk/) is an anglicization of the Greek term ἀδιάβατος "impassable" (used by Xenophon of rivers).
[src:combustion/adiabatic] It is used in the thermodynamic sense by Rankine (1866), and adopted by Maxwell in 1871 (explicitly attributing the term to Rankine).
[src:combustion/adiabatic] The etymological origin corresponds here to an impossibility of transfer of energy as heat and of transfer of matter across the wall.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] The Greek word ἀδιάβατος is formed from privative ἀ- ("not") and διαβατός, "passable", in turn deriving from διά ("through"), and βαῖνειν ("to walk, go, come").
[src:combustion/adiabatic] Furthermore, in atmospheric thermodynamics, a diabatic process is one in which heat is exchanged.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] An adiabatic process is the opposite – a process in which no heat is exchanged.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] The adiabatic process has been important for thermodynamics since its early days.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] It was important in the work of Joule because it provided a way of nearly directly relating quantities of heat and work.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] Energy can enter or leave a thermodynamic system enclosed by walls that prevent mass transfer only as heat or work.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] Therefore, a quantity of work in such a system can be related almost directly to an equivalent quantity of heat in a cycle of two limbs.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] The first limb is an isochoric adiabatic work process increasing the system's internal energy; the second, an isochoric and workless heat transfer returning the system to its original state.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] Accordingly, Rankine measured quantity of heat in units of work, rather than as a calorimetric quantity.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] In 1854, Rankine used a quantity that he called "the thermodynamic function" that later was called entropy, and at that time he wrote also of the "curve of no transmission of heat", which he later called an adiabatic curve.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] Besides its two isothermal limbs, Carnot's cycle has two adiabatic limbs.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] For the foundations of thermodynamics, the conceptual importance of this was emphasized by Bryan, by Carathéodory, and by Born.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] The reason is that calorimetry presupposes a type of temperature as already defined before the statement of the first law of thermodynamics, such as one based on empirical scales.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] Such a presupposition involves making the distinction between empirical temperature and absolute temperature.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] Rather, the definition of absolute thermodynamic temperature is best left till the second law is available as a conceptual basis.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] In the eighteenth century, the law of conservation of energy was not yet fully formulated or established, and the nature of heat was debated.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] One approach to these problems was to regard heat, measured by calorimetry, as a primary substance that is conserved in quantity.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] By the middle of the nineteenth century, it was recognized as a form of energy, and the law of conservation of energy was thereby also recognized.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] The view that eventually established itself, and is currently regarded as right, is that the law of conservation of energy is a primary axiom, and that heat is to be analyzed as consequential.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] In this light, heat cannot be a component of the total energy of a single body because it is not a state variable but, rather, a variable that describes a transfer between two bodies.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] The adiabatic process is important because it is a logical ingredient of this current view.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] This present article is written from the viewpoint of macroscopic thermodynamics, and the word *adiabatic* is used in this article in the traditional way of thermodynamics, introduced by Rankine.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] It is pointed out in the present article that, for example, if a compression of a gas is rapid, then there is little time for heat transfer to occur, even when the gas is not adiabatically isolated by a definite wall.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] In this sense, a rapid compression of a gas is sometimes approximately or loosely said to be *adiabatic*, though often far from isentropic, even when the gas is not adiabatically isolated by a definite wall.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] Some authors, like Pippard, recommend using "adiathermal" to refer to processes where no heat-exchange occurs (such as Joule expansion), and "adiabatic" to reversible quasi-static adiathermal processes (so that rapid compression of a gas is *not* "adiabatic").
[src:combustion/adiabatic] And Laidler has summarized the complicated etymology of "adiabatic".
[src:combustion/adiabatic] Quantum mechanics and quantum statistical mechanics, however, use the word *adiabatic* in a very different sense, one that can at times seem almost opposite to the classical thermodynamic sense.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] In quantum theory, the word *adiabatic* can mean something perhaps near isentropic, or perhaps near quasi-static, but the usage of the word is very different between the two disciplines.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] On the one hand, in quantum theory, if a perturbative element of compressive work is done almost infinitely slowly (that is to say quasi-statically), it is said to have been done *adiabatically*.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] The idea is that the shapes of the eigenfunctions change slowly and continuously, so that no quantum jump is triggered, and the change is virtually reversible.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] While the occupation numbers are unchanged, nevertheless there is change in the energy levels of one-to-one corresponding, pre- and post-compression, eigenstates.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] Thus a perturbative element of work has been done without heat transfer and without introduction of random change within the system.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] In that theory, such a rapid change is said not to be *adiabatic*, and the contrary word *diabatic* is applied to it.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] Recent research suggests that the power absorbed from the perturbation corresponds to the rate of these non-adiabatic transitions.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] This corresponds to the classical process of energy transfer in the form of heat, but with the relative time scales reversed in the quantum case.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] Quantum adiabatic processes occur over relatively long time scales, while classical adiabatic processes occur over relatively short time scales.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] It should also be noted that the concept of 'heat' (in reference to the quantity of thermal energy transferred) breaks down at the quantum level, and the specific form of energy (typically electromagnetic) must be considered instead.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] The small or negligible absorption of energy from the perturbation in a quantum adiabatic process provides a good justification for identifying it as the quantum analogue of adiabatic processes in classical thermodynamics, and for the reuse of the term.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] In classical thermodynamics, such a rapid change would still be called adiabatic because the system is adiabatically isolated, and there is no transfer of energy as heat.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] The strong irreversibility of the change, due to viscosity or other entropy production, does not impinge on this classical usage.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] Thus for a mass of gas, in macroscopic thermodynamics, words are so used that a compression is sometimes loosely or approximately said to be adiabatic if it is rapid enough to avoid significant heat transfer, even if the system is not adiabatically isolated.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] But in quantum statistical theory, a compression is not called adiabatic if it is rapid, even if the system is adiabatically isolated in the classical thermodynamic sense of the term.
[src:combustion/adiabatic] The words are used differently in the two disciplines, as stated just above.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] In an internal combustion engine or industrial furnace, the air–fuel ratio is an important measure for anti-pollution and performance-tuning reasons.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] If exactly enough air is provided to completely burn all of the fuel (**stoichiometric combustion**), the ratio is known as the **stoichiometric mixture**, often abbreviated to **stoich**.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] Ratios lower than stoichiometric (where the fuel is in excess) are considered "rich".
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] Rich mixtures are less efficient, but may produce more power and burn cooler.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] Ratios higher than stoichiometric (where the air is in excess) are considered "lean".
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] Lean mixtures are more efficient but may cause higher temperatures, which can lead to the formation of nitrogen oxides.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] Some engines are designed with features to allow lean-burn.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] For precise air–fuel ratio calculations, the oxygen content of combustion air should be specified because of different air density due to different altitude or intake air temperature, possible dilution by ambient water vapor, or enrichment by oxygen additions.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] An **air-fuel ratio meter** monitors the air–fuel ratio of an internal combustion engine.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] Also called **air–fuel ratio gauge**, **air–fuel meter**, or **air–fuel gauge**, it reads the voltage output of an oxygen sensor, sometimes also called **AFR sensor** or lambda sensor.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] The original narrow-band oxygen sensors became factory installed standard in the late 1970s and early 1980s.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] In recent years a newer and much more accurate wide-band sensor, though more expensive, has become available.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] Most stand-alone narrow-band meters have 10 LEDs and some have more.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] Also common, narrow band meters in round housings with the standard mounting 52 and 67 mm (2+1⁄16 and 2+5⁄8 in) diameters, as other types of car 'gauges'.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] Analogue 'needle' style gauges are also available.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] In theory, a stoichiometric mixture has just enough air to completely burn the available fuel.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] In practice, this is never quite achieved, due primarily to the very short time available in an internal combustion engine for each combustion cycle.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] Most of the combustion process is completed in approximately 2 milliseconds at an engine speed of 6,000 revolutions per minute (100 revolutions per second, or 10 milliseconds per revolution of the crankshaft.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] For a four-stroke engine this would mean 5 milliseconds for each piston stroke, and 20 milliseconds to complete one 720 degree Otto cycle).
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] This is the time that elapses from the spark plug firing until 90% of the fuel–air mix is combusted, typically some 80 degrees of crankshaft rotation later.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] Catalytic converters are designed to work best when the exhaust gases passing through them are the result of nearly perfect combustion.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] A perfectly stoichiometric mixture burns very hot and can damage engine components if the engine is placed under high load at this fuel–air mixture.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] Due to the high flame temperatures at this mixture, detonation is possible under high load.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] (Detonation is known as knocking or pinging).
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] Such detonation can cause serious engine damage as the uncontrolled burning of the fuel-air mix can create very high pressures in the cylinder.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] As a consequence, stoichiometric mixtures are only used under light to low-moderate load conditions.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] For acceleration and high-load conditions, a richer mixture (lower air–fuel ratio) is used to produce cooler combustion products and so avoid overheating of the cylinder head, and thus prevent detonation.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] The stoichiometric mixture for a gasoline engine is the ideal ratio of air to fuel that burns all fuel with no excess air.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] For gasoline fuel, the stoichiometric air–fuel mixture is about 14.7:1 i.e. for every one gram of fuel, 14.7 grams of air are required.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] Any mixture greater than 14.7:1 is considered a lean mixture; any less than 14.7:1 is a rich mixture – given perfect (ideal) "test" fuel (gasoline consisting of solely *n*-heptane and iso-octane).
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] In reality, most fuels consist of a combination of heptane, octane, a handful of other alkanes, plus additives including detergents, and possibly oxygenators such as MTBE (methyl *tert*-butyl ether) or ethanol/methanol.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] These compounds all alter the stoichiometric ratio, with most of the additives pushing the ratio downward (oxygenators bring extra oxygen to the combustion event in liquid form that is released at the time of combustions; for MTBE-laden fuel, a stoichiometric ratio can be as low as 14.1:1).
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] Vehicles that use an oxygen sensor or other feedback loops to control fuel to air ratio (lambda control), compensate automatically for this change in the fuel's stoichiometric rate by measuring the exhaust gas composition and controlling fuel volume.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] Vehicles that use oxygen sensors can monitor the air–fuel ratio with an air–fuel ratio meter.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] In the typical air to natural gas combustion burner, a double-cross limit strategy is employed to ensure ratio control.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] The strategy involves adding the opposite flow feedback into the limiting control of the respective gas (air or fuel).
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] This assures ratio control within an acceptable margin.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] There are other terms commonly used when discussing the mixture of air and fuel in internal combustion engines.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] Air-fuel ratio is the ratio between the *mass* of air and the mass of fuel in the air-fuel mix at any given moment.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] The mass is the mass of all constituents that compose the air or fuel, whether they take part in the combustion or not.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] For pure octane the stoichiometric mixture is approximately 15.1:1, or *λ* of 1.00 exactly.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] In naturally aspirated engines powered by octane, maximum power is frequently reached at AFRs ranging from 12.5 to 13.3:1 or *λ* of 0.850 to 0.901.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] The air-fuel ratio of 12:1 is considered as the maximum output ratio, whereas the air-fuel ratio of 16:1 is considered as the maximum fuel economy ratio.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] Air–fuel equivalence ratio, *λ* (lambda), is the ratio of actual AFR to stoichiometry for a given mixture.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] *λ* = 1.0 is at stoichiometry, rich mixtures *λ* < 1.0, and lean mixtures *λ* > 1.0.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] There is a direct relationship between *λ* and AFR.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] To calculate AFR from a given *λ*, multiply the measured *λ* by the stoichiometric AFR for that fuel.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] Alternatively, to recover *λ* from an AFR, divide AFR by the stoichiometric AFR for that fuel.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] Because the composition of common fuels varies seasonally, and because many modern vehicles can handle different fuels when tuning, it makes more sense to talk about *λ* values rather than AFR.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] Most practical AFR devices actually measure the amount of residual oxygen (for lean mixes) or unburnt hydrocarbons (for rich mixtures) in the exhaust gas.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] The **fuel–air equivalence ratio**, *Φ* (phi), of a system is defined as the ratio of the fuel-to-oxidizer ratio to the stoichiometric fuel-to-oxidizer ratio.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] where *m* represents the mass, *n* represents a number of moles, subscript st stands for stoichiometric conditions.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] The advantage of using equivalence ratio over fuel–oxidizer ratio is that it takes into account (and is therefore independent of) both mass and molar values for the fuel and the oxidizer.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] Consider, for example, a mixture of one mole of ethane (C 2H 6) and one mole of oxygen (O 2).
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] To compare it with the equivalence ratio, we need to determine the fuel–oxidizer ratio of ethane and oxygen mixture.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] This is not the case if one uses fuel–oxidizer ratio, which takes different values for different mixtures.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] In industrial fired heaters, power plant steam generators, and large gas-fired turbines, the more common terms are percent excess combustion air and percent stoichiometric air.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] For example, excess combustion air of 15 percent means that 15 percent more than the required stoichiometric air (or 115 percent of stoichiometric air) is being used.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] A combustion control point can be defined by specifying the percent excess air (or oxygen) in the oxidant, or by specifying the percent oxygen in the combustion product.
[src:combustion/air-fuel-ratio] An air–fuel ratio meter may be used to measure the percent oxygen in the combustion gas, from which the percent excess oxygen can be calculated from stoichiometry and a mass balance for fuel combustion.
[src:combustion/air] The **atmosphere of Earth** consists of a layer of mixed gas (commonly referred to as **air**) that is retained by gravity, surrounding the Earth's surface.
[src:combustion/air] It contains variable quantities of suspended aerosols and particulates that create weather features such as clouds and hazes.
[src:combustion/air] The atmosphere serves as a protective buffer between the Earth's surface and outer space.
[src:combustion/air] It shields the surface from most meteoroids and ultraviolet solar radiation, reduces diurnal temperature variation – the temperature extremes between day and night, and keeps it warm through heat retention via the greenhouse effect.
[src:combustion/air] The atmosphere redistributes heat and moisture among different regions via air currents, and provides the chemical and climate conditions that allow life to exist and evolve on Earth.
[src:combustion/air] By mole fraction (i.e., by quantity of molecules), dry air contains 78.08% nitrogen, 20.95% oxygen, 0.93% argon, 0.04% carbon dioxide, and small amounts of other trace gases (see Composition below for more detail).
[src:combustion/air] Air also contains a variable amount of water vapor, on average around 1% at sea level, and 0.4% over the entire atmosphere.
[src:combustion/air] Earth's primordial atmosphere consisted of gases accreted from the solar nebula, but the composition changed significantly over time, affected by many factors such as volcanism, outgassing, impact events, weathering and the evolution of life (particularly the photoautotrophs).
[src:combustion/air] In the present day, human activity has contributed to atmospheric changes, such as climate change (mainly through deforestation and fossil-fuel–related global warming), ozone depletion and acid deposition.
[src:combustion/air] The atmosphere has a mass of about 5.15×1018 kg, three quarters of which is within about 11 km (6.8 mi; 36,000 ft) of the surface.
[src:combustion/air] The atmosphere becomes thinner with increasing altitude, with no definite boundary between the atmosphere and outer space.
[src:combustion/air] The Kármán line at 100 km (62 mi) is often used as a conventional definition of the edge of space.
[src:combustion/air] Several layers can be distinguished in the atmosphere based on characteristics such as temperature and composition, namely the troposphere, stratosphere, mesosphere, thermosphere (formally the ionosphere), and exosphere.
[src:combustion/air] Air composition, temperature and atmospheric pressure vary with altitude.
[src:combustion/air] Air suitable for use in photosynthesis by terrestrial plants and respiration of terrestrial animals is found within the troposphere.
[src:combustion/air] The study of Earth's atmosphere and its processes is called atmospheric science (aerology), and includes multiple subfields, such as climatology and atmospheric physics.
[src:combustion/air] Early pioneers in the field include Léon Teisserenc de Bort and Richard Assmann.
[src:combustion/air] The study of the historic atmosphere is called paleoclimatology.
[src:combustion/air] The three major constituents of Earth's atmosphere are nitrogen, oxygen, and argon.
[src:combustion/air] Water vapor accounts for roughly 0.25% of the atmosphere by mass.
[src:combustion/air] The remaining gases are often referred to as trace gases, among which are other greenhouse gases, principally carbon dioxide, methane, nitrous oxide, and ozone.
[src:combustion/air] Besides argon, other noble gases, neon, helium, krypton, and xenon are also present.
[src:combustion/air] Filtered air includes trace amounts of many other chemical compounds.
[src:combustion/air] Many substances of natural origin may be present in locally and seasonally variable small amounts as aerosols in an unfiltered air sample, including dust of mineral and organic composition, pollen and spores, sea spray, and volcanic ash.
[src:combustion/air] Various industrial pollutants also may be present as gases or aerosols, such as chlorine (elemental or in compounds), fluorine compounds, and elemental mercury vapor.
[src:combustion/air] Sulfur compounds such as hydrogen sulfide and sulfur dioxide (SO2) may be derived from natural sources or from industrial air pollution.
[src:combustion/air] The average molecular weight of dry air, which can be used to calculate densities or to convert between mole fraction and mass fraction, is about 28.946 or 28.964 g/mol.
[src:combustion/air] This is decreased when the air is humid.
[src:combustion/air] Up to an altitude of around 100 km (62 mi), atmospheric turbulence mixes the component gases so that their relative concentrations remain the same.
[src:combustion/air] There exists a transition zone from roughly 80 to 120 km (50 to 75 mi) where this turbulent mixing gradually yields to molecular diffusion.
[src:combustion/air] The latter process forms the heterosphere where the relative concentration of lighter gases increase with altitude.
[src:combustion/air] In general, air pressure and density decrease with altitude in the atmosphere.
[src:combustion/air] However, temperature has a more complicated profile with altitude and may remain relatively constant or even increase with altitude in some regions (see the temperature section).
[src:combustion/air] Because the general pattern of the temperature/altitude profile, or lapse rate, is constant and measurable by means of instrumented balloon soundings, the temperature behavior provides a useful metric to distinguish atmospheric layers.
[src:combustion/air] The exosphere is the outermost layer of Earth's atmosphere (though it is so tenuous that some scientists consider it to be part of interplanetary space rather than part of the atmosphere).
[src:combustion/air] It extends from the thermopause (also known as the "exobase") at the top of the thermosphere to a poorly defined boundary with the solar wind and interplanetary medium.
[src:combustion/air] The altitude of the exobase varies from about 500 kilometres (310 mi; 1,600,000 ft) to about 1,000 kilometres (620 mi) in times of higher incoming solar radiation.
[src:combustion/air] The upper limit varies depending on the definition.
[src:combustion/air] Various authorities consider it to end at about 10,000 kilometres (6,200 mi) or about 190,000 kilometres (120,000 mi)—about halfway to the moon, where the influence of Earth's gravity is about the same as radiation pressure from sunlight.
[src:combustion/air] The geocorona visible in the far ultraviolet (caused by neutral hydrogen) extends to at least 100,000 kilometres (62,000 mi).
[src:combustion/air] This layer is mainly composed of extremely low densities of hydrogen, with limited amounts of helium, carbon dioxide, and nascent oxygen closer to the exobase.
[src:combustion/air] The atoms and molecules are so far apart that they can travel hundreds of kilometres without colliding with one another.
[src:combustion/air] Thus, the exosphere no longer behaves like a gas, and the particles constantly escape into space.
[src:combustion/air] These free-moving particles follow ballistic trajectories and may migrate in and out of the magnetosphere or the solar wind.
[src:combustion/air] Every second, the Earth loses about 3 kg of hydrogen, 50 g of helium, and much smaller amounts of other constituents.
[src:combustion/air] The exosphere is too far above Earth for meteorological phenomena to be possible.
[src:combustion/air] The exosphere contains many of the artificial satellites that orbit Earth.
[src:combustion/air] The thermosphere is the second-highest layer of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:combustion/air] It extends from the mesopause (which separates it from the mesosphere) at an altitude of about 80 km (50 mi) up to the thermopause at an altitude range of 500–1000 km (310–620 mi).
[src:combustion/air] The height of the thermopause varies considerably due to changes in solar activity.
[src:combustion/air] The passage of the dusk and dawn solar terminator creates background density perturbations up to a factor of two through this layer, forming a dominant feature in this region.
[src:combustion/air] Because the thermopause lies at the lower boundary of the exosphere, it is also referred to as the exobase.
[src:combustion/air] Overlapping the thermosphere, from 50 to 600 kilometres (31 to 373 mi) above Earth's surface, is the ionosphere – a region of enhanced plasma density.
[src:combustion/air] The temperature of the thermosphere gradually increases with height and can rise as high as 1500 °C (2700 °F), though the gas molecules are so far apart that its temperature in the usual sense is not very meaningful.
[src:combustion/air] This temperature increase is caused by absorption of ionizing UV and X-ray emission from the Sun.
[src:combustion/air] The air is so rarefied that an individual molecule (of oxygen, for example) travels an average of 1 kilometre (0.62 mi; 3300 ft) between collisions with other molecules.
[src:combustion/air] Although the thermosphere has a high proportion of molecules with high energy, it would not feel hot to a human in direct contact, because its density is too low to conduct a significant amount of energy to or from the skin.
[src:combustion/air] This layer is completely cloudless and free of water vapor.
[src:combustion/air] However, non-hydrometeorological phenomena such as the aurora borealis and aurora australis are occasionally seen in the thermosphere at an altitude of around 100 km (62 mi).
[src:combustion/air] The colors of the aurora are linked to the properties of the atmosphere at the altitude they occur.
[src:combustion/air] The most common is the green aurora, which comes from atomic oxygen in the 1S state, and occurs at altitudes from 120 to 400 km (75 to 250 mi).
[src:combustion/air] The International Space Station orbits in the thermosphere, between 370 and 460 km (230 and 290 mi).
[src:combustion/air] It is this layer where many of the satellites orbiting the Earth are present.
[src:combustion/air] The mesosphere is the third highest layer of Earth's atmosphere, occupying the region above the stratosphere and below the thermosphere.
[src:combustion/air] It extends from the stratopause at an altitude of about 50 km (31 mi) to the mesopause at 80–85 km (50–53 mi) above sea level.
[src:combustion/air] Temperatures drop with increasing altitude to the mesopause that marks the top of this middle layer of the atmosphere.
[src:combustion/air] It is the coldest place on Earth and has an average temperature around −85 °C (−120 °F; 190 K).
[src:combustion/air] Because the atmosphere absorbs sound waves at a rate that is proportional to the square of the frequency, audible sounds from the ground do not reach the mesosphere.
[src:combustion/air] Infrasonic waves can reach this altitude, but they are difficult to emit at a high power level.
[src:combustion/air] Just below the mesopause, the air is so cold that even the very scarce water vapor at this altitude can condense into polar-mesospheric noctilucent clouds of ice particles.
[src:combustion/air] These are the highest clouds in the atmosphere and may be visible to the naked eye if sunlight reflects off them about an hour or two after sunset or similarly before sunrise.
[src:combustion/air] They are most readily visible when the Sun is around 4 to 16 degrees below the horizon.
[src:combustion/air] Lightning-induced discharges known as transient luminous events (TLEs) occasionally form in the mesosphere above tropospheric thunderclouds.
[src:combustion/air] The mesosphere is also the layer where most meteors and satellites burn up upon atmospheric entrance.
[src:combustion/air] It is too high above Earth to be accessible to jet-powered aircraft and balloons, and too low to permit orbital spacecraft.
[src:combustion/air] The mesosphere is mainly accessed by sounding rockets and rocket-powered aircraft.
[src:combustion/air] The stratosphere is the second-lowest layer of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:combustion/air] It lies above the troposphere and is separated from it by the tropopause.
[src:combustion/air] This layer extends from the top of the troposphere at roughly 12 km (7.5 mi) above Earth's surface to the stratopause at an altitude of about 50 to 55 km (31 to 34 mi).
[src:combustion/air] 99% of the total mass of the atmosphere lies below 30 km (19 mi), and the atmospheric pressure at the top of the stratosphere is roughly 1/1000 the pressure at sea level.
[src:combustion/air] It contains the ozone layer, which is the part of Earth's atmosphere that contains relatively high concentrations of that gas.
[src:combustion/air] The stratosphere defines a layer in which temperatures rise with increasing altitude.
[src:combustion/air] This rise in temperature is caused by the absorption of ultraviolet radiation (UV) from the Sun by the ozone layer, which restricts turbulence and mixing.
[src:combustion/air] Although the temperature may be −80 °C (−110 °F; 190 K) at the tropopause, the top of the stratosphere is much warmer, and may be just below 0 °C.
[src:combustion/air] This layer is unique to the Earth; neither Mars nor Venus have a stratosphere because of low abundances of oxygen in their atmospheres.
[src:combustion/air] The stratospheric temperature profile creates very stable atmospheric conditions, so the stratosphere lacks the weather-producing air turbulence that is so prevalent in the troposphere.
[src:combustion/air] Consequently, the stratosphere is almost completely free of clouds and other forms of weather.
[src:combustion/air] However, polar stratospheric or nacreous clouds are occasionally seen in the lower part of this layer of the atmosphere where the air is coldest.
[src:combustion/air] The stratosphere is the highest layer that can be accessed by jet-powered aircraft.
[src:combustion/air] The troposphere is the lowest layer of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:combustion/air] It extends from Earth's surface to an average height of about 12 km (7.5 mi), although this altitude varies from about 9 km (5.6 mi) at the geographic poles to 17 km (11 mi) at the Equator, with some variation due to weather.
[src:combustion/air] The troposphere is bounded above by the tropopause, a boundary marked in most places by a temperature inversion (i.e. a layer of relatively warm air above a colder one), and in others by a zone that is isothermal with height.
[src:combustion/air] Although variations do occur, the temperature usually declines with increasing altitude in the troposphere because the troposphere is mostly heated through energy transfer from the surface.
[src:combustion/air] Thus, the lowest part of the troposphere (i.e.
[src:combustion/air] Earth's surface) is typically the warmest section of the troposphere.
[src:combustion/air] This promotes vertical mixing (hence, the origin of its name in the Greek word τρόπος, *tropos*, meaning "turn").
[src:combustion/air] The troposphere contains roughly 80% of the mass of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:combustion/air] The troposphere is denser than all its overlying layers because a larger atmospheric weight sits on top of the troposphere and causes it to be more severely compressed.
[src:combustion/air] Fifty percent of the total mass of the atmosphere is located in the lower 5.5 km (3.4 mi) of the troposphere.
[src:combustion/air] Nearly all atmospheric water vapor or moisture is found in the troposphere, so it is the layer where most of Earth's weather takes place.
[src:combustion/air] The ability of the atmosphere to retain water decreases as the temperature declines, so 90% of the water vapor is held in the lower part of the troposphere.
[src:combustion/air] It has basically all the weather-associated cloud genus types generated by active wind circulation, although very tall cumulonimbus thunder clouds can penetrate the tropopause from below and rise into the lower part of the stratosphere.
[src:combustion/air] Most conventional aviation activity takes place in the troposphere, and it is the only layer accessible by propeller-driven aircraft.
[src:combustion/air] Contrails are formed from jet engine water emission at altitudes where the atmospheric temperature is about −53 °C (−63 °F); typically around 7.7 km (4.8 mi) for modern engines.
[src:combustion/air] Above this altitude lies the heterosphere, which includes the exosphere and most of the thermosphere.
[src:combustion/air] Here, the chemical composition varies with altitude.
[src:combustion/air] is large compared with the size of motions that cause mixing.
[src:combustion/air] with the heavier ones, such as oxygen and nitrogen, present only near the bottom of the heterosphere.
[src:combustion/air] The upper part of the heterosphere is composed almost completely of hydrogen, the lightest element.
[src:combustion/air] The average temperature of the atmosphere at Earth's surface is 14 °C (57 °F; 287 K) or 15 °C (59 °F; 288 K), depending on the reference.
[src:combustion/air] The average atmospheric pressure at sea level is defined by the International Standard Atmosphere as 101325 pascals (760.00 Torr; 14.6959 psi; 760.00 mmHg).
[src:combustion/air] This is sometimes referred to as a unit of standard atmospheres (atm).
[src:combustion/air] Total atmospheric mass is 5.1480×1018 kg (1.13494×1019 lb), about 2.5% less than would be inferred from the average sea-level pressure and Earth's area of 51007.2 megahectares, this portion being displaced by Earth's mountainous terrain.
[src:combustion/air] Atmospheric pressure is the total weight of the air above unit area at the point where the pressure is measured.
[src:combustion/air] Thus air pressure varies with location and weather.
[src:combustion/air] Air pressure decreases exponentially with altitude at a rate that depends on the air temperature.
[src:combustion/air] The rate of decrease is determined by a temperature-dependent parameter called the scale height: for each increase in altitude by this height, the pressure decreases by a factor of *e* (the base of natural logarithms, approximately 2.718).
[src:combustion/air] For Earth, this value is typically 5.5 to 6 km for altitudes up to around 80 km (50 mi).
[src:combustion/air] However, the atmosphere is more accurately modeled with a customized equation for each layer that takes gradients of temperature, molecular composition, solar radiation and gravity into account.
[src:combustion/air] At heights over 100 km, the atmosphere is not well mixed, so each chemical species has its own scale height.
[src:combustion/air] At altitudes of 200 to 300 km, the combined scale height is 20 to 30 km.
[src:combustion/air] Even above the Kármán line, significant atmospheric effects such as auroras still occur.
[src:combustion/air] Meteors begin to glow in this region, though the larger ones may not burn up until they penetrate more deeply.
[src:combustion/air] The various layers of Earth's ionosphere, important to HF radio propagation, begin below 100 km and extend beyond 500 km.
[src:combustion/air] By comparison, the International Space Station typically orbit at 370–460 km, within the F-layer of the ionosphere, where they encounter enough atmospheric drag to require reboosts every few months, otherwise orbital decay will occur, resulting in a return to Earth.
[src:combustion/air] Depending on solar activity, satellites can experience noticeable atmospheric drag at altitudes as high as 600–800 km.
[src:combustion/air] Starting at sea level, the temperature decreases with altitude until reaching the stratosphere at around 11 km.
[src:combustion/air] Above, the temperature stabilizes over a large vertical distance.
[src:combustion/air] Starting above about 20 km, the temperature increases with height, due to heating within the ozone layer caused by the capture of significant ultraviolet radiation from the Sun by the molecular oxygen and ozone gas in this region.
[src:combustion/air] A second region of increasing temperature with altitude occurs at very high altitudes, in the aptly-named thermosphere above 90 km.
[src:combustion/air] During the night, the ground radiates more energy than it gains from the atmosphere.
[src:combustion/air] As energy is conducted from the nearby atmosphere to the cooler ground, it creates a temperature inversion where the local temperature increases with altitude up to around 1,000 m.
[src:combustion/air] For example, at sea level the speed of sound is 340 m/s.
[src:combustion/air] At the average temperature of the stratosphere, −60 °C, the speed of sound decreases to 290 m/s.
[src:combustion/air] Density is not measured directly but is calculated from measurements of temperature, pressure and humidity using the equation of state for air (a form of the ideal gas law).
[src:combustion/air] Atmospheric density decreases as the altitude increases.
[src:combustion/air] This variation can be approximately modeled using the barometric formula.
[src:combustion/air] More sophisticated models are used to predict the orbital decay of satellites.
[src:combustion/air] The average mass of the atmosphere is about 5 quadrillion (5×1015) tonnes or 1/1,200,000 the mass of Earth.
[src:combustion/air] According to the American National Center for Atmospheric Research, "The total mean mass of the atmosphere is 5.1480×1018 kg with an annual range due to water vapor of 1.2 or 1.5×1015 kg, depending on whether surface pressure or water vapor data are used; somewhat smaller than the previous estimate.
[src:combustion/air] Solar radiation (or sunlight) is the energy Earth receives from the Sun.
[src:combustion/air] Earth also emits radiation back into space, but at longer wavelengths that humans cannot see.
[src:combustion/air] As energy propagates through the atmosphere, it is impacted by the process of radiative transfer.
[src:combustion/air] That is, some of the incoming and emitted radiation is subject to absorption, emission, and scattering by the atmosphere.
[src:combustion/air] Another portion of the incident energy is reflected, with the two most important atmospheric reflectors being dust and clouds.
[src:combustion/air] Depending on the properties of the aerosol, clouds can reflect up to 70% of the incident radiation.
[src:combustion/air] Globally, clouds reflect 20% of the incoming energy, contributing two thirds of the planet's total albedo.
[src:combustion/air] In May 2017, glints of light, seen as twinkling from an orbiting satellite a million miles away, were found to be reflected light from ice crystals in the troposphere.
[src:combustion/air] When light passes through Earth's atmosphere, photons interact with it through *scattering*.
[src:combustion/air] If the light does not interact with the atmosphere, it is called *direct radiation* and is what you see if you were to look directly at the Sun.
[src:combustion/air] *Indirect radiation* is light that has been scattered in the atmosphere.
[src:combustion/air] For example, on an overcast day when you cannot see your shadow, there is no direct radiation reaching you, it has all been scattered.
[src:combustion/air] As another example, due to a phenomenon called Rayleigh scattering, shorter (blue) wavelengths scatter more easily than longer (red) wavelengths.
[src:combustion/air] This is why the sky looks blue; you are seeing scattered blue light.
[src:combustion/air] Because the Sun is close to the horizon, the Sun's rays pass through more atmosphere than normal before reaching your eye.
[src:combustion/air] Much of the blue light has been scattered out, leaving the red light in a sunset.
[src:combustion/air] Different molecules absorb different wavelengths of radiation.
[src:combustion/air] For example, O2 and O3 absorb almost all radiation with wavelengths shorter than 300 nanometres.
[src:combustion/air] Water (H2O) absorbs at many wavelengths above 700 nm.
[src:combustion/air] When a molecule absorbs a photon, it increases the energy of the molecule.
[src:combustion/air] This heats the atmosphere, but the atmosphere also cools by emitting radiation, as discussed below.
[src:combustion/air] In astronomical spectroscopy, the absorption of specific frequencies by the atmosphere is referred to as telluric contamination.
[src:combustion/air] The combined absorption spectra of the gases in the atmosphere leave "windows" of low opacity, allowing the transmission of only certain bands of light.
[src:combustion/air] The optical window runs from around 300 nm (ultraviolet-C) up into the range humans can see, the visible spectrum (commonly called light), at roughly 400–700 nm and continues to the infrared to around 1100 nm.
[src:combustion/air] There are also infrared and radio windows that transmit some infrared and radio waves at longer wavelengths.
[src:combustion/air] For example, the radio window runs from about one centimetre to about eleven-metre waves.
[src:combustion/air] Because of its temperature, the atmosphere emits infrared radiation.
[src:combustion/air] For example, on clear nights Earth's surface cools down faster than on cloudy nights.
[src:combustion/air] This is because clouds (H2O) are strong absorbers and emitters of infrared radiation.
[src:combustion/air] This is also why it becomes colder at night at higher elevations.
[src:combustion/air] The greenhouse effect is directly related to this absorption and emission effect.
[src:combustion/air] Some gases in the atmosphere absorb and emit infrared radiation, but do not interact in this manner with sunlight in the visible spectrum.
[src:combustion/air] Common examples of these are CO2 and H2O.
[src:combustion/air] Without greenhouse gases in the atmosphere, the average temperature of Earth's surface would be a frozen −18 °C (0 °F), rather than the present comfortable average of 15 °C (59 °F).
[src:combustion/air] The refractive index of air is close to, but just greater than, 1.
[src:combustion/air] Systematic variations in the refractive index can lead to the bending of light rays over long optical paths.
[src:combustion/air] One example is that, under some circumstances, observers on board ships can see other vessels just over the horizon because light is refracted in the same direction as the curvature of Earth's surface.
[src:combustion/air] The refractive index of air depends on temperature, giving rise to refraction effects when the temperature gradient is large.
[src:combustion/air] An example of such effects is the mirage.
[src:combustion/air] The flow of air around the planet is divided into three main convection cells by latitude.
[src:combustion/air] Around the equator, the Hadley cell is driven by the rising flow of air along the equator.
[src:combustion/air] In the upper atmosphere, this air flows toward the poles.
[src:combustion/air] At mid latitudes, this circulation is reversed, with ground air flowing toward the poles with the Ferrel cell.
[src:combustion/air] Finally, in the high latitudes is the Polar cell, where air again rises and flows toward the poles.
[src:combustion/air] The interface between these cells is responsible for jet streams.
[src:combustion/air] These are narrow, fast moving bands that flow from west to east and typically form at an elevation of around 9,100 m (30,000 ft).
[src:combustion/air] Jet streams can shift around depending on conditions.
[src:combustion/air] They are strongest in winter, when the boundaries between hot and cold air are the most pronounced.
[src:combustion/air] In the middle latitudes, it is instabilities in the jet streams that are responsible for moving weather systems.
[src:combustion/air] As with the oceans, the Earth's atmosphere is subject to waves and tidal forces.
[src:combustion/air] These are triggered by non-uniform heating by the Sun, and by the daily solar cycle, respectively.
[src:combustion/air] Wave-like behavior can occur on a variety of scales, from smaller gravity waves that transfer momentum into the higher atmospheric layers, to much larger planetary waves, or Rossby waves.
[src:combustion/air] Atmospheric tides are periodic oscillations of the troposphere and stratosphere that transport energy to the upper atmosphere.
[src:combustion/air] The first atmosphere, during the Early Earth's Hadean eon, consisted of gases in the solar nebula, primarily hydrogen, and probably simple hydrides such as those now found in the gas giants (Jupiter and Saturn), notably water vapor, methane and ammonia.
[src:combustion/air] During this earliest era, the Moon-forming collision and numerous impacts with large meteorites heated the atmosphere, driving off the most volatile gases.
[src:combustion/air] The collision with Theia, in particular, melted and ejected large portions of Earth's mantle and crust and outgassed significant amounts of steam which eventually cooled and condensed to contribute to ocean water at the end of the Hadean.
[src:combustion/air] The increasing solidification of Earth's crust at the end of the Hadean closed off most of the advective heat transfer to the surface, causing the atmosphere to cool, which condensed most of the water vapor out of the air precipitating into a superocean.
[src:combustion/air] Further outgassing from volcanism, supplemented by gases introduced by huge asteroids during the Late Heavy Bombardment, created the subsequent Archean atmosphere, which consisted largely of nitrogen plus carbon dioxide, methane and inert gases.
[src:combustion/air] A major part of carbon dioxide emissions dissolved in water and reacted with metals such as calcium and magnesium during weathering of crustal rocks to form carbonates that were deposited as sediments.
[src:combustion/air] Water-related sediments have been found that date from as early as 3.8 billion years ago.
[src:combustion/air] About 3.4 billion years ago, nitrogen formed the major component of the then-stable "second atmosphere".
[src:combustion/air] The influence of the evolution of life has to be taken into account rather soon in the history of the atmosphere because hints of earliest life forms appeared as early as 3.5 billion years ago.
[src:combustion/air] How Earth at that time maintained a climate warm enough for liquid water and life, if the early Sun put out 30% lower solar radiance than today, is a puzzle known as the "faint young Sun paradox".
[src:combustion/air] The geological record however shows a continuous relatively warm surface during the complete early temperature record of Earth – with the exception of one cold glacial phase about 2.4 billion years ago.
[src:combustion/air] In the late Neoarchean, an oxygen-containing atmosphere began to develop, apparently due to a billion years of cyanobacterial photosynthesis (known as the Great Oxygenation Event), which have been found as stromatolite fossils from 2.7 billion years ago.
[src:combustion/air] The early basic carbon isotopy (isotope ratio proportions) strongly suggests conditions similar to the current, and that the fundamental features of the carbon cycle became established as early as 4 billion years ago.
[src:combustion/air] Ancient sediments in the Gabon dating from between about 2.15 and 2.08 billion years ago provide a record of Earth's dynamic oxygenation evolution.
[src:combustion/air] These fluctuations in oxygenation were likely driven by the Lomagundi-Jatuli Carbon Isotope Excursion.
[src:combustion/air] The constant re-arrangement of continents by plate tectonics influences the long-term evolution of the atmosphere by transferring carbon dioxide to and from large continental carbonate stores.
[src:combustion/air] Before this time, any oxygen produced by cyanobacterial photosynthesis would be readily removed by the oxidation of reducing substances on the Earth's surface, notably ferrous iron, sulfur and atmospheric methane.
[src:combustion/air] Free oxygen molecules did not start to accumulate in the atmosphere until the rate of production of oxygen began to exceed the availability of reductant materials that removed oxygen.
[src:combustion/air] This point signifies a shift from a reducing atmosphere to an oxidizing atmosphere.
[src:combustion/air] O2 showed major variations during the Proterozoic, including a billion-year period of euxinia, until reaching a steady state of more than 15% by the end of the Precambrian.
[src:combustion/air] The amount of oxygen in the atmosphere has fluctuated over the last 600 million years, reaching a peak of about 35% around 280 million years ago during the Carboniferous period, significantly higher than today's 21%.
[src:combustion/air] Two main processes govern changes in the atmosphere: the evolution of plants and their increasing role in carbon fixation, and the consumption of oxygen by rapidly diversifying animal faunae and also by plants for photorespiration and their own metabolic needs at night.
[src:combustion/air] Breakdown of pyrite and volcanic eruptions release sulfur into the atmosphere, which reacts and hence reduces oxygen in the atmosphere.
[src:combustion/air] However, volcanic eruptions also release carbon dioxide, which can fuel oxygenic photosynthesis by terrestrial and aquatic plants.
[src:combustion/air] The cause of the variation of the amount of oxygen in the atmosphere is not precisely understood.
[src:combustion/air] Periods with more oxygen in the atmosphere were often associated with more rapid development of animals.
[src:combustion/air] Since 1750, human activity, especially after the Industrial Revolution, has increased the concentrations of various greenhouse gases, most importantly carbon dioxide, methane and nitrous oxide.
[src:combustion/air] Greenhouse gas emissions, coupled with deforestation and destruction of wetlands via logging and land developments, have caused an observed rise in global temperatures, with the global average surface temperatures being 1.1 °C higher in the 2011–2020 decade than they were in 1850.
[src:combustion/air] It has raised concerns of man-made climate change, which can have significant environmental impacts such as sea level rise, ocean acidification, glacial retreat (which threatens water security), increasing extreme weather events and wildfires, ecological collapse and mass dying of wildlife.
[src:combustion/anthracite] The Coal Region of Northeastern Pennsylvania in the United States has the largest known deposits of anthracite coal in the world with an estimated reserve of seven billion short tons (6.35 billion metric tons).
[src:combustion/anthracite] China accounts for the majority of global production; other producers include Russia, Ukraine, North Korea, South Africa, Vietnam, Australia, Canada, and the United States.
[src:combustion/anthracite] The total production of anthracite worldwide in 2023 was 632 million short tons (573 million metric tons).
[src:combustion/anthracite] Anthracite is the most metamorphosed type of coal, but still represents low-grade metamorphism, as found in the anthracite of the Narragansett Basin in Rhode Island which is of greenschist metamorphic facies (muscovite-chlorite sub-facies).
[src:combustion/anthracite] The carbon content of anthracite is between 86% and 97%.
[src:combustion/anthracite] The term is applied to those varieties of coal which do not give off tarry or other hydrocarbon vapours when heated below their point of ignition.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Anthracite is difficult to ignite, and burns with a short, blue, and smokeless flame.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Anthracite is categorized into several grades.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Standard grade anthracite is used predominantly in power generation, and high grade (HG) and ultra high grade (UHG) are used predominantly in the metallurgy sector.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Anthracite accounts for about 1% of global coal reserves, and is mined in only a few countries around the world.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Anthracite derives from the Greek *anthrakítēs* (ἀνθρακίτης), literally "coal-like".
[src:combustion/anthracite] Other terms which refer to anthracite are **black coal**, **hard coal**, **stone coal**, **dark coal**, **coffee coal**, **blind coal** (in Scotland), **Kilkenny coal** (in Ireland), **crow coal** or **craw coal**, and **black diamond**.
[src:combustion/anthracite] **"Blue Coal"** is the term for a once-popular and trademarked brand of anthracite, mined by the Glen Alden Coal Company in Pennsylvania, and sprayed with a blue dye at the mine before shipping to its Northeastern U.S. markets to distinguish it from its competitors.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Culm has different meanings in British and American English.
[src:combustion/anthracite] In British English, culm is the imperfect anthracite, located predominantly north Devon and Cornwall, which was used as a pigment.
[src:combustion/anthracite] The term is also used to refer to some carboniferous rock strata found in both Britain and in the Rhenish hill countries, also known as the Culm Measures.
[src:combustion/anthracite] In Britain, it may also refer to coal exported from Britain during the 19th century.
[src:combustion/anthracite] In American English, "culm" refers to the waste or slack from anthracite mining, mostly dust and small pieces not suitable for use in home furnaces.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Anthracite is similar in appearance to the mineraloid jet and is sometimes used as a jet imitation.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Anthracite differs from ordinary bituminous coal by its greater hardness (2.75–3 on the Mohs scale), its higher relative density of 1.3–1.4, and luster, which is often semi-metallic with a mildly green reflection.
[src:combustion/anthracite] It contains a high percentage of fixed carbon and a low percentage of volatile matter.
[src:combustion/anthracite] It is also free from included soft or fibrous notches and does not soil the fingers when rubbed.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Anthracitization is the transformation of bituminous coal into anthracite.
[src:combustion/anthracite] The moisture content of fresh-mined anthracite generally is less than 15 percent.
[src:combustion/anthracite] The heat content of anthracite ranges from 26 to 33 MJ/kg (22 to 28 million Btu/short ton) on a moist, mineral-matter-free basis.
[src:combustion/anthracite] The heat content of anthracite coal consumed in the United States averages 29 MJ/kg (25 million Btu/ton), on the as-received basis, containing both inherent moisture and mineral matter.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Since the 1980s, anthracite refuse or mine waste has been used for coal power generation in a form of recycling.
[src:combustion/anthracite] The practice known as reclamation is being applied to culm piles antedating laws requiring mine owners to restore lands to their approximate original condition.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Anthracite is associated with strongly deformed sedimentary rocks that were subjected to higher pressures and temperatures (but short of metamorphic conditions) just as bituminous coal is generally associated with less deformed or flat-lying sedimentary rocks.
[src:combustion/anthracite] In the same way the anthracite region of South Wales is confined to the contorted portion west of Swansea and Llanelli, the central and eastern portions producing steam coal, coking coal and domestic house coals.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Anthracite shows some alteration by the development of secondary divisional planes and fissures so that the original stratification lines are not always easily seen.
[src:combustion/anthracite] The thermal conductivity is also higher; a lump of anthracite feels perceptibly colder when held in the warm hand than a similar lump of bituminous coal at the same temperature.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Anthracite has a history of use in blast furnaces for iron smelting; however, it lacked the pore space of metallurgical coke, which eventually replaced anthracite.
[src:combustion/anthracite] In southwest Wales, anthracite has been burned as a domestic fuel since at least medieval times, when it was mined near Saundersfoot.
[src:combustion/anthracite] More recently, large-scale mining of anthracite took place across the western part of the South Wales Coalfield until the late 20th century.
[src:combustion/anthracite] In the United States, anthracite coal history began in 1790 in Pottsville, Pennsylvania, with the discovery of coal made by the hunter Necho Allen in what is now known as the Coal Region.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Legend has it that Allen fell asleep at the base of Broad Mountain and woke to the sight of a large fire because his campfire had ignited an outcrop of anthracite coal.
[src:combustion/anthracite] By the late 18th century, it was known in the United States that anthracite could be burnt, but the techniques required to do so were unknown.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Anthracite differs from wood and bituminous coal in that it has a higher ignition temperature and needs a fresh air draft from the bottom to burn.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Several claims are made about who "first" burnt anthracite coal in the United States around this time, and all such claims originate from Pennsylvania.
[src:combustion/anthracite] The city of Pottsville, Pennsylvania claims that their town was founded around an anthracite-fired iron furnace purchased by John Potts in 1806, which was built on the Schuylkill River in 1795.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Hagner recalls in his 1869 book that an unnamed employee of Josiah White and Erskine Hazard accidentally burnt anthracite in their rolling mill at the Falls of the Schuylkill River (after much failed experimentation with burning anthracite) at some point between 1812 and 1815.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Judge Jesse Fell is claimed to be the first person to burn anthracite for the purposes of residential heating in the USA in Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania on 11 February 1808.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Judge Fell used an open grate in his fireplace to burn anthracite, as an experiment to prove that it was a viable residential heating fuel.
[src:combustion/anthracite] In spring 1808, John and Abijah Smith shipped the first commercially mined load of anthracite down the Susquehanna River from Plymouth, Pennsylvania, marking the birth of commercial anthracite mining in the United States.
[src:combustion/anthracite] From that first mine, production rose to an all-time high of over 100 million tons in 1917.
[src:combustion/anthracite] The difficulty of igniting anthracite inhibited its early use, especially in blast furnaces for smelting iron.
[src:combustion/anthracite] With the development of the hot blast in 1828, which used waste heat to preheat combustion air, anthracite became a preferred fuel, accounting for 45% of US pig iron production within 15 years.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Anthracite iron smelting was later displaced by coke.
[src:combustion/anthracite] From the late 19th century until the 1950s, anthracite was the most popular fuel for heating homes and other buildings in the northern US, until it was supplanted by oil-burning systems, and more recently natural gas systems.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Many large public buildings, such as schools, were heated with anthracite-burning furnaces through the 1980s.
[src:combustion/anthracite] During the American Civil War, Confederate blockade runners used anthracite as a smokeless fuel for their boilers to avoid revealing their position to the blockaders.
[src:combustion/anthracite] The invention of the Wootten firebox enabled locomotives to directly burn anthracite efficiently, particularly waste culm.
[src:combustion/anthracite] The advertisements featured a white-clad woman named Phoebe Snow and poems containing lines like "My gown stays white / From morn till night / Upon the road of Anthracite".
[src:combustion/anthracite] Similarly, the Great Western Railway in the UK was able to use its access to anthracite (it dominated the anthracite region) to earn a reputation for efficiency and cleanliness unmatched by other UK companies.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Large quantities of anthracite for power purposes were formerly exported from South Wales to France, Switzerland and parts of Germany.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Commercial anthracite mining in Wales ceased in 2013, although a few large open cast sites remain, along with some relatively small drift mining operations.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Commercial anthracite mining is still ongoing in Pennsylvania; the state produced a "total of 4,614,391 tons of [anthracite] coal, predominately from surface coal mines" in 2015.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Anthracite generally costs two to six times as much as regular coal.
[src:combustion/anthracite] In June 2008, the wholesale cost of anthracite was US$150/short ton, falling to $107/ton in 2021; it makes up 1% of U.S. coal production.
[src:combustion/anthracite] The principal use of anthracite today is for a domestic fuel in either hand-fired stoves or automatic stoker furnaces.
[src:combustion/anthracite] It delivers high energy per its weight and burns cleanly with little soot, making it ideal for this purpose.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Its high value makes it prohibitively expensive for power plant use.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Other uses include the fine particles used as filter media, and as an ingredient in charcoal briquettes.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Anthracite was an authorised fuel in terms of the United Kingdom's Clean Air Act 1993, meaning that it could be used within a designated Smoke Control Area such as the central London boroughs.
[src:combustion/anthracite] As of 2023, China mines by far the largest share of global anthracite production, accounting for more than three-quarters of global output.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Most Chinese production is of standard-grade anthracite, which is used in power generation.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Increased demand in China has made that country into a net importer of the fuel, mostly from Vietnam, another major producer of anthracite for power generation, although increasing domestic consumption in Vietnam means that exports may be scaled back.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Current U.S. anthracite production averages around five million tons per year.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Of that, about 1.8 million tons were mined in the state of Pennsylvania.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Mining of anthracite coal continues to this day in eastern Pennsylvania, and contributes up to 1% to the gross state product.
[src:combustion/anthracite] More than 2,000 people were employed in the mining of anthracite coal in 1995.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Most of the mining as of that date involved reclaiming coal from slag heaps (waste piles from past coal mining) at nearby closed mines.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Some underground anthracite coal is also being mined.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Countries producing HG and UHG anthracite include Russia and South Africa.
[src:combustion/anthracite] HG and UHG anthracite are used as a coke or coal substitute in various metallurgical coal applications (sintering, PCI, direct BF charge, pelletizing).
[src:combustion/anthracite] It plays an important role in cost reduction in the steel making process and is also used in production of ferroalloys, silicomanganese, calcium carbide and silicon carbide.
[src:combustion/anthracite] South Africa exports lower-quality, higher-ash anthracite to Brazil to be used in steel-making.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Anthracite is processed into different sizes by what is commonly referred to as a breaker.
[src:combustion/anthracite] The large coal is raised from the mine and passed through breakers with toothed rolls to reduce the lumps to smaller pieces.
[src:combustion/anthracite] The smaller pieces are separated into different sizes by a system of graduated sieves, placed in descending order.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Sizing is necessary for different types of stoves and furnaces.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Anthracite is classified into three grades, depending on its carbon content.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Standard grade is used as a domestic fuel and in industrial power-generation.
[src:combustion/anthracite] The rarer higher grades of anthracite are purer – i.e., they have a higher carbon content – and are used in steel-making and other segments of the metallurgical industries.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Anthracite is divided by size mainly into applications that need lumps (typically larger than 10 mm) – various industrial processes where it replaces metallurgical coke, and domestic fuel – and those that need fines (less than 10 mm), such as sintering and pelletising.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Lump, steamboat, egg and stove coals, the latter in two or three sizes, all three being above 1+1⁄2 in (38 mm) size on round-hole screens.
[src:combustion/anthracite] High grade (HG) and ultra high grade (UHG) anthracite are the highest grades of anthracite coal.
[src:combustion/anthracite] They are the purest forms of coal, having the highest degree of coalification, the highest carbon count and energy content and the fewest impurities (moisture, ash and volatiles).
[src:combustion/anthracite] High grade and ultra high grade anthracite are harder than standard grade anthracite, and have a higher relative density.
[src:combustion/anthracite] An example of a chemical formula for high-grade anthracite would be C240H90O4NS, representing 94% carbon.
[src:combustion/anthracite] UHG anthracite typically has a minimum carbon content of 95%.
[src:combustion/anthracite] They can also be used in water purification and domestically as a smokeless fuel.
[src:combustion/anthracite] HG and UHG anthracite account for a small percentage of the total anthracite market.
[src:combustion/anthracite] The major producing countries are Russia, Ukraine, Vietnam, South Africa and the US.
[src:combustion/anthracite] The primary sizes used in the United States for domestic heating are Chestnut, Pea, Buckwheat and Rice, with Chestnut and Rice being the most popular.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Chestnut and Pea are used in hand fired furnaces while the smaller Rice and Buckwheat are used in automatic stoker furnaces.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Rice is currently the most sought-after size due to the ease of use and popularity of that type of furnace.
[src:combustion/anthracite] In South Wales, a less elaborate classification is adopted, but great care is exercised in hand-picking and cleaning the coal from particles of pyrites in the higher qualities known as best malting coals, which are used for kiln-drying malt.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Anthracite dust can be made into briquettes and is sold in the United Kingdom under trade names such as Phurnacite, Ancit and Taybrite.
[src:combustion/anthracite] On the opposite end from high-grade anthracite coal, semianthracite coal is defined as a coal which is intermediate between anthracite coal and bituminous coal, and particularly a coal which approaches anthracite in nonvolatile character.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Historically, from time to time, underground seams of coal have caught fire, often from careless or unfortunate mining activities.
[src:combustion/anthracite] The pocket of ignited coal is fed oxygen by vent paths that have not yet been discovered.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Commonly, exhaust vents in populated areas are soon sensed and are sealed while vents in uninhabited areas remain undiscovered.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Occasionally, vents are discovered via fumes sensed by passers-by, often in forested areas.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Attempts to extinguish those remaining have at times been futile, and several such combustion areas exist today.
[src:combustion/anthracite] The existence of an underground combustion site can sometimes be identified in the winter where fallen snow is seen to be melted by the warmth conducted from below.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Proposals for harnessing this heat as geothermal energy have not been successful.
[src:combustion/anthracite] A vein of anthracite that caught fire in Centralia, Pennsylvania, in 1962 has been burning ever since, turning the once-thriving borough into a ghost town.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Geologically, the largest most concentrated anthracite deposit in the world is found in the Lackawanna Coal Mine in northeastern Pennsylvania, United States in and around Scranton, Pennsylvania.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Locally called the Coal Region, the deposit contains 480 square miles (1,200 km2) of coal-bearing rock which originally held 22.8 billion short tons (20.68 billion tonnes) of anthracite.
[src:combustion/anthracite] The geographic region is roughly 100 miles (161 km) in length and 30 miles (48 km) in width.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Because of historical mining and development of the lands overlying the coal, it is estimated that 7 billion short tons (6.3 billion tonnes) of minable reserves remain.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Other areas of the United States also contain several smaller deposits of anthracite, such as those historically mined in Crested Butte, Colorado.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Among current producers, Russia, China, Poland, and Ukraine have the largest estimated recoverable reserves of anthracite.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Other countries with substantial reserves include Vietnam and North Korea.
[src:combustion/anthracite] The Groundhog Anthracite Deposit in British Columbia, Canada, is the world's largest previously undeveloped anthracite deposit.
[src:combustion/anthracite] It is owned by the Australian publicly traded company Atrum Coal and has 1.57 billion tonnes of high grade anthracite.
[src:combustion/anthracite] Anthracites of newer Tertiary or Cretaceous age are found in the Crowsnest Pass part of the Rocky Mountains in Canada and at various places in the Andes in Peru.
[src:combustion/combustion] Combustion is often a complicated sequence of elementary radical reactions.
[src:combustion/combustion] Solid fuels, such as wood and coal, first undergo endothermic pyrolysis to produce gaseous fuels whose combustion then supplies the heat required to produce more of them.
[src:combustion/combustion] Combustion is often hot enough that incandescent light in the form of either glowing or a flame is produced.
[src:combustion/combustion] A simple example can be seen in the combustion of hydrogen and oxygen into water vapor, a reaction which is commonly used to fuel rocket engines.
[src:combustion/combustion] Uncatalyzed combustion in air requires relatively high temperatures.
[src:combustion/combustion] Complete combustion is stoichiometric concerning the fuel, where there is no remaining fuel, and ideally, no residual oxidant.
[src:combustion/combustion] Thermodynamically, the chemical equilibrium of combustion in air is overwhelmingly on the side of the products.
[src:combustion/combustion] However, complete combustion is almost impossible to achieve, since the chemical equilibrium is not necessarily reached, or may contain unburnt products such as carbon monoxide, hydrogen and even carbon (soot or ash).
[src:combustion/combustion] Thus, the produced smoke is usually toxic and contains unburned or partially oxidized products.
[src:combustion/combustion] Any combustion at high temperatures in atmospheric air, which is 78 percent nitrogen, will also create small amounts of several nitrogen oxides, commonly referred to as NOx, since the combustion of nitrogen is thermodynamically favored at high, but not low temperatures.
[src:combustion/combustion] Since burning is rarely clean, fuel gas cleaning or catalytic converters may be required by law.
[src:combustion/combustion] Fires occur naturally, ignited by lightning strikes or by volcanic products.
[src:combustion/combustion] Combustion (fire) was the first controlled chemical reaction discovered by humans, in the form of campfires and bonfires, and continues to be the main method to produce energy for humanity.
[src:combustion/combustion] Usually, the fuel is hydrogen, hydrocarbons (a compound with a mixture of hydrogen and carbon), or more complicated mixtures such as wood that contain partially oxidized hydrocarbons.
[src:combustion/combustion] The thermal energy produced from the combustion of either fossil fuels such as coal or oil, or from renewable fuels such as firewood, is harvested for diverse uses such as cooking, production of electricity or industrial or domestic heating.
[src:combustion/combustion] Combustion is also currently the only reaction used to power rockets.
[src:combustion/combustion] Combustion is also used to destroy (incinerate) waste, both nonhazardous and hazardous.
[src:combustion/combustion] Oxidants for combustion have high oxidation potential and include atmospheric or pure oxygen, chlorine, fluorine, chlorine trifluoride, nitrous oxide and nitric acid.
[src:combustion/combustion] For instance, hydrogen burns in chlorine to form hydrogen chloride with the liberation of heat and light characteristic of combustion.
[src:combustion/combustion] Although usually not catalyzed, combustion can be catalyzed by platinum or vanadium, as in the contact process.
[src:combustion/combustion] In complete combustion, the reactant burns in oxygen and produces a limited number of products.
[src:combustion/combustion] When a hydrocarbon burns in oxygen, the reaction will primarily yield carbon dioxide and water.
[src:combustion/combustion] When elements are burned, the products are primarily the most common oxides.
[src:combustion/combustion] Carbon will yield carbon dioxide, sulfur will yield sulfur dioxide, and iron will yield iron(III) oxide.
[src:combustion/combustion] Nitrogen is not considered to be a combustible substance when oxygen is the oxidant.
[src:combustion/combustion] Still, small amounts of various nitrogen oxides (commonly designated NO *x* species) form when the air is the oxidative.
[src:combustion/combustion] Combustion is not necessarily favorable to the maximum degree of oxidation, and it can be temperature-dependent.
[src:combustion/combustion] For example, sulfur trioxide is not produced quantitatively by the combustion of sulfur.
[src:combustion/combustion] NO*x* species appear in significant amounts above about 2,800 °F (1,540 °C), and more is produced at higher temperatures.
[src:combustion/combustion] The amount of NO*x* is also a function of oxygen excess.
[src:combustion/combustion] In most industrial applications and in fires, air is the source of oxygen (O 2).
[src:combustion/combustion] In the air, each mole of oxygen is mixed with approximately 3.71 mol of nitrogen.
[src:combustion/combustion] Nitrogen does not take part in combustion, but at high temperatures, some nitrogen will be converted to NO *x* (mostly NO, with much smaller amounts of NO 2).
[src:combustion/combustion] On the other hand, when there is insufficient oxygen to combust the fuel completely, some fuel carbon is converted to carbon monoxide, and some of the hydrogens remain unreacted.
[src:combustion/combustion] A complete set of equations for the combustion of a hydrocarbon in the air, therefore, requires an additional calculation for the distribution of oxygen between the carbon and hydrogen in the fuel.
[src:combustion/combustion] The amount of air required for complete combustion is known as the "theoretical air" or "stoichiometric air".
[src:combustion/combustion] The amount of air above this value actually needed for optimal combustion is known as the "excess air", and can vary from 5% for a natural gas boiler, to 40% for anthracite coal, to 300% for a gas turbine.
[src:combustion/combustion] Incomplete combustion will occur when there is not enough oxygen to allow the fuel to react completely to produce carbon dioxide and water.
[src:combustion/combustion] It also happens when the combustion is quenched by a heat sink, such as a solid surface or flame trap.
[src:combustion/combustion] As is the case with complete combustion, water is produced by incomplete combustion; however, carbon and carbon monoxide are produced instead of carbon dioxide.
[src:combustion/combustion] For most fuels, such as diesel oil, coal, or wood, pyrolysis occurs before combustion.
[src:combustion/combustion] In incomplete combustion, products of pyrolysis remain unburnt and contaminate the smoke with noxious particulate matter and gases.
[src:combustion/combustion] Partially oxidized compounds are also a concern; partial oxidation of ethanol can produce harmful acetaldehyde, and carbon can produce toxic carbon monoxide.
[src:combustion/combustion] The designs of combustion devices can improve the quality of combustion, such as burners and internal combustion engines.
[src:combustion/combustion] Further improvements are achievable by catalytic after-burning devices (such as catalytic converters) or by the simple partial return of the exhaust gases into the combustion process.
[src:combustion/combustion] Such devices are required by environmental legislation for cars in most countries.
[src:combustion/combustion] They may be necessary to enable large combustion devices, such as thermal power stations, to reach legal emission standards.
[src:combustion/combustion] The degree of combustion can be measured and analyzed with test equipment.
[src:combustion/combustion] HVAC contractors, firefighters and engineers use combustion analyzers to test the efficiency of a burner during the combustion process.
[src:combustion/combustion] Also, the efficiency of an internal combustion engine can be measured in this way, and some U.S. states and local municipalities use combustion analysis to define and rate the efficiency of vehicles on the road today.
[src:combustion/combustion] Carbon monoxide is one of the products from incomplete combustion.
[src:combustion/combustion] The formation of carbon monoxide produces less heat than formation of carbon dioxide so complete combustion is greatly preferred especially as carbon monoxide is a poisonous gas.
[src:combustion/combustion] When breathed, carbon monoxide takes the place of oxygen and combines with some of the hemoglobin in the blood, rendering it unable to transport oxygen.
[src:combustion/combustion] These oxides combine with water and oxygen in the atmosphere, creating nitric acid and sulfuric acids, which return to Earth's surface as acid deposition, or "acid rain".
[src:combustion/combustion] Acid deposition harms aquatic organisms and kills trees.
[src:combustion/combustion] Due to its formation of certain nutrients that are less available to plants such as calcium and phosphorus, it reduces the productivity of the ecosystem and farms.
[src:combustion/combustion] An additional problem associated with nitrogen oxides is that they, along with hydrocarbon pollutants, contribute to the formation of ground level ozone, a major component of smog.
[src:combustion/combustion] Breathing carbon monoxide causes headache, dizziness, vomiting, and nausea.
[src:combustion/combustion] If carbon monoxide levels are high enough, humans become unconscious or die.
[src:combustion/combustion] Exposure to moderate and high levels of carbon monoxide over long periods is positively correlated with the risk of heart disease.
[src:combustion/combustion] People who survive severe carbon monoxide poisoning may suffer long-term health problems.
[src:combustion/combustion] Carbon monoxide from the air is absorbed in the lungs which then binds with hemoglobin in human's red blood cells.
[src:combustion/combustion] This reduces the capacity of red blood cells that carry oxygen throughout the body.
[src:combustion/combustion] Smoldering is the slow, low-temperature, flameless form of combustion, sustained by the heat evolved when oxygen directly attacks the surface of a condensed-phase fuel.
[src:combustion/combustion] It is a typically incomplete combustion reaction.
[src:combustion/combustion] Solid materials that can sustain a smoldering reaction include coal, cellulose, wood, cotton, tobacco, peat, duff, humus, synthetic foams, charring polymers (including polyurethane foam) and dust.
[src:combustion/combustion] Common examples of smoldering phenomena are the initiation of residential fires on upholstered furniture by weak heat sources (e.g., a cigarette, a short-circuited wire) and the persistent combustion of biomass behind the flaming fronts of wildfires.
[src:combustion/combustion] Spontaneous combustion is a type of combustion that occurs by self-heating (increase in temperature due to exothermic internal reactions), followed by thermal runaway (self-heating which rapidly accelerates to high temperatures) and finally, ignition.
[src:combustion/combustion] For example, phosphorus self-ignites at room temperature without the application of heat.
[src:combustion/combustion] Organic materials undergoing bacterial composting can generate enough heat to reach the point of combustion.
[src:combustion/combustion] Combustion resulting in a turbulent flame is the most used for industrial applications (e.g. gas turbines, gasoline engines, etc.) because the turbulence helps the mixing process between the fuel and oxidizer.
[src:combustion/combustion] In such an environment, the thermal and flow transport dynamics can behave quite differently than in normal gravity conditions (e.g., a candle's flame takes the shape of a sphere.).
[src:combustion/combustion] Combustion processes that happen in very small volumes are considered micro-combustion.
[src:combustion/combustion] The high surface-to-volume ratio increases specific heat loss.
[src:combustion/combustion] Quenching distance plays a vital role in stabilizing the flame in such combustion chambers.
[src:combustion/combustion] If the stoichiometric combustion takes place using air as the oxygen source, the nitrogen present in the air (Atmosphere of Earth) can be added to the equation (although it does not react) to show the stoichiometric composition of the fuel in air and the composition of the resultant flue gas.
[src:combustion/combustion] Treating all non-oxygen components in air as nitrogen gives a "nitrogen" to oxygen ratio of 3.77, i.e.
[src:combustion/combustion] The stoichiometric composition of methane in air is 1 / (1 + 2 + 7.54) = 9.49% vol.
[src:combustion/combustion] Various other substances begin to appear in significant amounts in combustion products when the flame temperature is above about 1600 K.
[src:combustion/combustion] When excess air is used, nitrogen may oxidize to NO and, to a much lesser extent, to NO 2.
[src:combustion/combustion] CO forms by disproportionation of CO2, and H 2 and OH form by disproportionation of H2O.
[src:combustion/combustion] For example, when 1 mol of propane is burned with 28.6 mol of air (120% of the stoichiometric amount), the combustion products contain 3.3% O 2.
[src:combustion/combustion] At 1400 K, the equilibrium combustion products contain 0.03% NO and 0.002% OH.
[src:combustion/combustion] Diesel engines are run with an excess of oxygen to combust small particles that tend to form with only a stoichiometric amount of oxygen, necessarily producing nitrogen oxide emissions.
[src:combustion/combustion] Both the United States and European Union enforce limits to vehicle nitrogen oxide emissions, which necessitate the use of special catalytic converters or treatment of the exhaust with urea (see Diesel exhaust fluid).
[src:combustion/combustion] The incomplete (partial) combustion of a hydrocarbon with oxygen produces a gas mixture containing mainly CO 2, CO, H2O, and H 2.
[src:combustion/combustion] Such gas mixtures are commonly prepared for use as protective atmospheres for the heat-treatment of metals and for gas carburizing.
[src:combustion/combustion] When *z* falls below roughly 50% of the stoichiometric value, CH 4 can become an important combustion product; when *z* falls below roughly 35% of the stoichiometric value, elemental carbon may become stable.
[src:combustion/combustion] The products of incomplete combustion can be calculated with the aid of a material balance, together with the assumption that the combustion products reach equilibrium.
[src:combustion/combustion] For example, in the combustion of one mole of propane (C 3H 8) with four moles of O 2, seven moles of combustion gas are formed, and *z* is 80% of the stoichiometric value.
[src:combustion/combustion] These three equations are insufficient in themselves to calculate the combustion gas composition.
[src:combustion/combustion] For example, at 1200 K the value of *Keq* is 0.728.
[src:combustion/combustion] Carbon becomes a stable phase at 1200 K and 1 atm pressure when z is less than 30% of the stoichiometric value, at which point the combustion products contain more than 98% H 2 and CO and about 0.5% CH 4.
[src:combustion/combustion] Substances or materials which undergo combustion are called fuels.
[src:combustion/combustion] The most common examples are natural gas, propane, kerosene, diesel, petrol, charcoal, coal, wood, etc.
[src:combustion/combustion] Combustion of a liquid fuel in an oxidizing atmosphere actually happens in the gas phase.
[src:combustion/combustion] It is the vapor that burns, not the liquid.
[src:combustion/combustion] Therefore, a liquid will normally catch fire only above a certain temperature: its flash point.
[src:combustion/combustion] The flash point of liquid fuel is the lowest temperature at which it can form an ignitable mix with air.
[src:combustion/combustion] It is the minimum temperature at which there is enough evaporated fuel in the air to start combustion.
[src:combustion/combustion] Combustion of gaseous fuels may occur through one of four distinctive types of burning: diffusion flame, premixed flame, autoignitive reaction front, or as a detonation.
[src:combustion/combustion] The type of burning that actually occurs depends on the degree to which the fuel and oxidizer are mixed prior to heating: for example, a diffusion flame is formed if the fuel and oxidizer are separated initially, whereas a premixed flame is formed otherwise.
[src:combustion/combustion] Similarly, the type of burning also depends on the pressure: a detonation, for example, is an autoignitive reaction front coupled to a strong shock wave giving it its characteristic high-pressure peak and high detonation velocity.
[src:combustion/combustion] Efficient process heating requires recovery of the largest possible part of a fuel's heat of combustion into the material being processed.
[src:combustion/combustion] There are many avenues of loss in the operation of a heating process.
[src:combustion/combustion] Typically, the dominant loss is sensible heat leaving with the offgas (i.e., the flue gas).
[src:combustion/combustion] The temperature and quantity of offgas indicates its heat content (enthalpy), so keeping its quantity low minimizes heat loss.
[src:combustion/combustion] In a perfect furnace, the combustion air flow would be matched to the fuel flow to give each fuel molecule the exact amount of oxygen needed to cause complete combustion.
[src:combustion/combustion] However, in the real world, combustion does not proceed in a perfect manner.
[src:combustion/combustion] Unburned fuel (usually CO and H 2) discharged from the system represents a heating value loss (as well as a safety hazard).
[src:combustion/combustion] Since combustibles are undesirable in the offgas, while the presence of unreacted oxygen there presents minimal safety and environmental concerns, the first principle of combustion management is to provide more oxygen than is theoretically needed to ensure that all the fuel burns.
[src:combustion/combustion] For methane (CH 4) combustion, for example, slightly more than two molecules of oxygen are required.
[src:combustion/combustion] The second principle of combustion management, however, is to not use too much oxygen.
[src:combustion/combustion] The correct amount of oxygen requires three types of measurement: first, active control of air and fuel flow; second, offgas oxygen measurement; and third, measurement of offgas combustibles.
[src:combustion/combustion] For each heating process, there exists an optimum condition of minimal offgas heat loss with acceptable levels of combustibles concentration.
[src:combustion/combustion] Minimizing excess oxygen pays an additional benefit: for a given offgas temperature, the NOx level is lowest when excess oxygen is kept lowest.
[src:combustion/combustion] Adherence to these two principles is furthered by making material and heat balances on the combustion process.
[src:combustion/combustion] The material balance directly relates the air/fuel ratio to the percentage of O 2 in the combustion gas.
[src:combustion/combustion] The heat balance relates the heat available for the charge to the overall net heat produced by fuel combustion.
[src:combustion/combustion] Additional material and heat balances can be made to quantify the thermal advantage from preheating the combustion air, or enriching it in oxygen.
[src:combustion/combustion] Combustion in oxygen is a chain reaction in which many distinct radical intermediates participate.
[src:combustion/combustion] The high energy required for initiation is explained by the unusual structure of the dioxygen molecule.
[src:combustion/combustion] The lowest-energy configuration of the dioxygen molecule is a stable, relatively unreactive diradical in a triplet spin state.
[src:combustion/combustion] Bonding can be described with three bonding electron pairs and two antibonding electrons, with spins aligned, such that the molecule has nonzero total angular momentum.
[src:combustion/combustion] Most fuels, on the other hand, are in a singlet state, with paired spins and zero total angular momentum.
[src:combustion/combustion] Interaction between the two is quantum mechanically a "forbidden transition", i.e. possible with a very low probability.
[src:combustion/combustion] To initiate combustion, energy is required to force dioxygen into a spin-paired state, or singlet oxygen.
[src:combustion/combustion] This intermediate is extremely reactive.
[src:combustion/combustion] The energy is supplied as heat, and the reaction then produces additional heat, which allows it to continue.
[src:combustion/combustion] Combustion of hydrocarbons is thought to be initiated by hydrogen atom abstraction (not proton abstraction) from the fuel to oxygen, to give a hydroperoxide radical (HOO).
[src:combustion/combustion] This reacts further to give hydroperoxides, which break up to give hydroxyl radicals.
[src:combustion/combustion] There are a great variety of these processes that produce fuel radicals and oxidizing radicals.
[src:combustion/combustion] Oxidizing species include singlet oxygen, hydroxyl, monatomic oxygen, and hydroperoxyl.
[src:combustion/combustion] Such intermediates are short-lived and cannot be isolated.
[src:combustion/combustion] However, non-radical intermediates are stable and are produced in incomplete combustion.
[src:combustion/combustion] An example is acetaldehyde produced in the combustion of ethanol.
[src:combustion/combustion] An intermediate in the combustion of carbon and hydrocarbons, carbon monoxide, is of special importance because it is a poisonous gas, but also economically useful for the production of syngas.
[src:combustion/combustion] Solid and heavy liquid fuels also undergo a great number of pyrolysis reactions that give more easily oxidized, gaseous fuels.
[src:combustion/combustion] These reactions are endothermic and require constant energy input from the ongoing combustion reactions.
[src:combustion/combustion] A lack of oxygen or other improperly designed conditions result in these noxious and carcinogenic pyrolysis products being emitted as thick, black smoke.
[src:combustion/combustion] The rate of combustion is the amount of a material that undergoes combustion over a period of time.
[src:combustion/combustion] It can be expressed in grams per second (g/s) or kilograms per second (kg/s).
[src:combustion/combustion] Detailed descriptions of combustion processes, from the chemical kinetics perspective, require the formulation of large and intricate webs of elementary reactions.
[src:combustion/combustion] For instance, combustion of hydrocarbon fuels typically involve hundreds of chemical species reacting according to thousands of reactions.
[src:combustion/combustion] The inclusion of such mechanisms within computational flow solvers still represents a pretty challenging task mainly in two aspects.
[src:combustion/combustion] First, the number of degrees of freedom (proportional to the number of chemical species) can be dramatically large; second, the source term due to reactions introduces a disparate number of time scales which makes the whole dynamical system stiff.
[src:combustion/combustion] As a result, the direct numerical simulation of turbulent reactive flows with heavy fuels soon becomes intractable even for modern supercomputers.
[src:combustion/combustion] Therefore, a plethora of methodologies have been devised for reducing the complexity of combustion mechanisms without resorting to high detail levels.
[src:combustion/combustion] The kinetic modelling may be explored for insight into the reaction mechanisms of thermal decomposition in the combustion of different materials by using for instance Thermogravimetric analysis.
[src:combustion/combustion] Assuming perfect combustion conditions, such as complete combustion under adiabatic conditions (i.e., no heat loss or gain), the adiabatic combustion temperature can be determined.
[src:combustion/combustion] The formula that yields this temperature is based on the first law of thermodynamics and takes note of the fact that the heat of combustion is used entirely for heating the fuel, the combustion air or oxygen, and the combustion product gases (commonly referred to as the *flue gas*).
[src:combustion/combustion] The adiabatic combustion temperature (also known as the *adiabatic flame temperature*) increases for higher heating values and inlet air and fuel temperatures and for stoichiometric air ratios approaching one.
[src:combustion/combustion] Most commonly, the adiabatic combustion temperatures for coals are around 2,200 °C (3,992 °F) (for inlet air and fuel at ambient temperatures and for $\lambda =1.0$ ), around 2,150 °C (3,902 °F) for oil and 2,000 °C (3,632 °F) for natural gas.
[src:combustion/combustion] In industrial fired heaters, power station steam generators, and large gas-fired turbines, the more common way of expressing the usage of more than the stoichiometric combustion air is *percent excess combustion air*.
[src:combustion/combustion] For example, excess combustion air of 15 percent means that 15 percent more than the required stoichiometric air is being used.
[src:combustion/combustion] Combustion instabilities are typically violent pressure oscillations in a combustion chamber.
[src:combustion/combustion] These pressure oscillations can be as high as 180 dB, and long-term exposure to these cyclic pressure and thermal loads reduces the life of engine components.
[src:combustion/combustion] In rockets, such as the F1 used in the Saturn V program, instabilities led to massive damage to the combustion chamber and surrounding components.
[src:combustion/combustion] This problem was solved by re-designing the fuel injector.
[src:combustion/combustion] In liquid jet engines, the droplet size and distribution can be used to attenuate the instabilities.
[src:combustion/combustion] Combustion instabilities are a major concern in ground-based gas turbine engines because of NO*x* emissions.
[src:combustion/combustion] The tendency is to run lean, an equivalence ratio less than 1, to reduce the combustion temperature and thus reduce the NO*x* emissions; however, running the combustion lean makes it very susceptible to combustion instability.
[src:combustion/combustion] where q' is the heat release rate perturbation and p' is the pressure fluctuation.
[src:combustion/combustion] When the heat release oscillations are in phase with the pressure oscillations, the Rayleigh Index is positive and the magnitude of the thermoacoustic instability is maximised.
[src:combustion/combustion] On the other hand, if the Rayleigh Index is negative, then thermoacoustic damping occurs.
[src:combustion/combustion] The Rayleigh Criterion implies that thermoacoustic instability can be optimally controlled by having heat release oscillations 180 degrees out of phase with pressure oscillations at the same frequency.
